product_title: Lima Smart & Private Cloud Device for Mac, PC, Smartphone and Tablet, Blue
review_headline: Don't rush to buy this - still in development
review_body: Avoid this device for now - it's not a finished product.  Tried to install and the Lima was not detected on the main local network. After switching to a different network entirely, the device was detected and made a system update.  Support site is a circular process of moving between two pages that repeat the same information (turn it off and on again, check if you have internet). Rinse and repeat. I did get real human support at one point, but they only repeated the information already shown on the website.  There's no status light on the device so it's hard to tell if it's alive and working properly which is a very poor design decision. You'd think that a light that came on to show power or readiness would be straightforward to include on a device costing $150.  After running for 20 minutes the Lima is quite warm, perhaps even a little hot. I don't know how well it will last with continuous use as a passively cooled device, though after leaving on for a day it did not get any hotter.  Of note is that during the installation process, you are given the chance to add mobile devices, but if you skip this, there is no obvious way to add them later from within the Lima software. You need to go to their website to find the address in order to download the app onto your phone, plus you need to install some third party crash reporting application in order to use the beta app. Also pay attention to the default settings on the phone app - on Android they default to using Wifi + Data to synchronize everything, so if you are on a limited data plan and don't check the settings fully, you could find yourself going over your monthly limit.  If you don't have administrator access to your router, there are two possibilities:  1. Your Lima won't be connected - see the problem I encountered above.  2. You won't be able to set up any port forwarding for the Lima. This means your data will pass through their servers encrypted; as there is no security audit yet on what they do, I guessyou have to take their word for what's going on for encryption. I also don't know what this would mean long term if they decided to turn their servers off or they change business models - maybe you'd need a subscription to keep going when they realize that they need to keep selling devices to keep the servers on. The whole thing is not so clearly explained, and it feels less like you own the device, rather that you have it on loan while they exist.  On the local network transfer speeds look decent, though not fantastic; the real test will be from a remote location.  ***Update*** Depending on what your remote location is, you may not have access to the Lima. I tried in a corporate managed network environment and could not access my Lima; enable tethering on my phone and connect to the tethered network and the Lima pops up. Depending on how you plan to use your Lima, you may not be able to connect to it from all locations - keep this in mind before you buy it as you may not be able to access from a remote location.  For $150 it's not worth it - keep in mind you need to bring your own storage to the table in order to use the Lima, and once the drive is in use on the Lima, you can't unplug it and move the storage to another location and access the same files.  If they continue to add features and capabilities in the future, then it could reach the promised potential, but at the moment you are buying a promise of future functionality rather than a fully realized product that's ready to go.

product_title: Sentey GS-2342 Noir 3mm Thick Gaming Mouse Pad, 11.7 X 8.55 Inch
review_headline: One flaw that keeps it from being anything more than "okay"

product_title: Logitech HD Pro Webcam C920, 1080p Widescreen Video Calling and Recording
review_headline: Best HD Webcam but NO SUPPORT FOR MAC?!
review_body:
Here's the thing. This camera is the best HD webcam out there. Better than Microsoft's even. But it has a massive issue: it is NOT supported on the Mac (OS X). Seriously Logitech? It's just absolutely ridiculous they wouldn't support Mac. It's stupid even - I mean, don't they wanna sell more cameras and make more money? -

On a Mac, the camera will work as a generic webcam device with Skype. It also works with Wirecast. You can record with Quicktime too - but you won't get any of the setting goodness needed to get the best out of it. Download the Logitech Camera Settings app from Logitech from the AppStore and you will get a bit more. There's an app called Webcam Settings too (3rd party - $7.99) which will give you even more control... but this all feels too hacky... not officially supported. Also, for my life, I wasn't able to make this camera be recognized by Adobe Premiere 2015 or by iMovie so it's pretty unusable for me...

review_headline: Initially good for the price, but don't expect it to last very long
review_body: I was looking for a laptop mainly for gaming and for school, and it fits both needs. For this price, this laptop can run big games like Counter Strike: Global Offensive, Skyrim, Fallout New Vegas, Garry's Mod, Rocket League, and more, all at 100 fps on average! This is the best cheap option out there. I also really love the new Windows 10 OS. It's simple to use, and all in all pretty aesthetically appealing. The only flaws are that it has a slow boot-up, due to the lack of a solid state drive, and occasionally the internet is slow as well, but maybe it's just mine. I highly recommend this, and I took one star off just because of the boot-up.  EDIT: It's about a year and 3 months after I bought it, and it is not holding up well. I didn't expect it to hold up perfectly for so long, but at this point it is really really slow. I had to dock another star due to ho poorly it is holding up.

Applications seem to run smoothly and instantly. The product itself is heavier than expected, but in a good way. The back feels a little cheaper but that is to be expected. Overall you can not ask for a better performing tablet for the price. I would recommend to anyone!

product_title: Dragon Touch X10 10" Octa Core Android Tablet PC, 1GB RAM 16GB Nand Flash, IPS Display 1366x768
review_body: I bought this because I needed an Android device for development.  However, after unboxing, configuring, and installing some apps on this device, I really don't think I'll be using it much.  I have a year and a half old iPad mini with Retina Display, and I've already noticed several things about this device that annoy me in comparison to the iPad.  First, the display quality on this is terrible.  Aside from the low resolution, it looks like everything is grainy and over-sharpened - even the default wallpaper. Contrast on edges look artificially high.  It gets really hot while charging, using the provided wall wart.  It arrived 97% charged, but even just charging that last 3%, it was slightly uncomfortable to hold and use while charging.  The way the keyboard scales to the screen dimensions make it clunky and difficult to use.  If you plan do do a lot of typing with this device, definitely get a Bluetooth keyboard.  It also doesn't identify itself to Google properly.  I got an email from Google saying that I signed into my account with a Sony Ericsson Xperia X10.  And it was set to a Chinese time zone when I received it.  Other than that, it's slower to boot than the iPad, makes settings hard to find (I had to dig for a while to figure out how to check for updates), and the whole concept of not all apps being displayed on the homescreen / having to tap something special to view what's installed is really weird coming from iOS.  It didn't detect the settings properly for my Exchange account.  So yeah, a lot of disappointments so far, but what it has going for it is that it works, it runs Android, and it's inexpensive.  But it in no way even comes close to competing with even the least expensive previous model of Apple equipment.

product_title: Plantronics .Audio 355 Multimedia Headset
review_headline: I've found the headsets to be very comfortable to wear for long durations of time (sometimes the ...
review_body:
Over the past 3 years I've had 2 sets of these headphones as my primary mic/speakers on work laptops. Both sets were supplied by my employer so I won't show up as a verified purchaser.

I've found the headsets to be very comfortable to wear for long durations of time (sometimes the bulk of the business day) and found the audio and mic capabilities perfectly suited for what I was doing - teleconferencing via Webex/Skype etc.

The only reason this is not a 5 star review is a significant one; both sets have snapped after 1-1.5 years use. The small plastic "slider" that allows you to extend the headset seems to be the weak part here. I don't pull these things apart far to get them on my head, and I definitely don't have them set too small for my head, but both sets have died the same way. Looking for an alternative rather than a third set from my employer for now.

product_title: iBenzer MKC01GD Macaron Series Keyboard Cover for MacBook Pro 13" 15" 17" (with or without Retina Display) MacBook Air 13" and iMac Wireless Keyboard, Gold
review_body: I had previously had another keyboard protector from another brand, I believe, and while it was great and lasted a long time, this one is just FANTASTIC!  I love the fit over the keys and within the groove of the keyboard as a whole.  The "caps lock" transparent hole actually aligns with the light, so now I can see when the caps lock is on (the previous one was misaligned and I couldn't see the light unless the room was dark).  I love the raised key markers, like on the "f" and "j' and right arrow buttons.  The color is such a nice muted gold.  It doesn't make the keys "stick" down when you type.  I don't mind the logo on the space bar at all.  Feels very durable and of good quality.  Since I anticipate having this for a while, I can't complain at the price.  I would definitely recommend this to anybody with a MacBook Pro, and I would most definitely repurchase this again! Just a note--the promotion at the time I purchased this was $1.00 off when you bought 1 or more.  I didn't receive that discount, even though it said it would be applied at checkout, so I don't know how that was supposed to work. Update--the gold color is fading quite noticeably on the left-hand's side of the keyboard.  It's turning this grey-blue color.  It hasn't been through excessive wear but the base cover is still very nice and functional.  Color is just fading.

product_title: iGadgitz Aluminium Adjustable Portable Tablet & Smartphone Folding Holder Stand
review_headline: Aluminum Multi-Angle Adjustable/Folding Tablet & Phone Stand, from 'iGadgitz'
review_body:
This is my favorite design of tablet and phone Stand. The same seemingly identical model stand is currently sold by a number of different Sellers at varying prices; this one is from iGadgitz.

This is made of silver colored Aluminum in a matte finish (also available in Black). The rear stand is a rigid plastic (silicone?) and gives good stability.

Very adjustable through a wide range of angles. Extremely stable once it 'locks'. Not too heavy to travel with, and it folds pretty flat in a briefcase, travel bag, or even a coat pocket.

I really like this simple, well designed little stand. I have an almost identical model from another Seller and it's held up well for over a year of daily use.

Sample sent for testing and impartial consumer review. This works great, and as I said I've owned an almost identical model for over a year and been very pleased with it.

I hope this is helpful as you comparison shop for portable tablet stands. Happy travels, everybody.

product_title: Microsoft Designer Bluetooth Mouse
review_headline: I dig this mouse, but would make a couple minor improvements if I could.
review_body:
I bought this mouse to use with my laptop away from home, so I was looking for something portable, sturdy and reliable (but really when aren't you looking for these qualities in things...) but at a low price. So I looked and considered several different mice, including this one. Honestly I really wanted the Apple Magic Mouse, but did not want to pay that much since I wasn't going to use it very often. That's when I came across this one, which I saw had decent reviews, Bluetooth, and most importantly was decently priced thanks to Amazon's Warehouse Deals. When I got the mouse I was a little surprised at just how short it is, it very thin compared to say a standard mouse you'd see bundled with a desktop, but not small like a travel mouse (not sure how to really express that in a different way). One feature that is mentioned with this mouse is the blue-track laser. Now I can't give you specifics compared to a standard red laser, but I've used this mouse on all kinds of surfaces without a mouse pad over the past few weeks, and have not experienced any problems. The reasons for me this gets 4 stars instead of 5 is that it feels a bit more "plastic" than I'd prefer and the mouse buttons are a little sensitive for my taste. The mouse has a nice rubberized feel, and is very light, but just feels like thin plastic when you hold it, almost like it flexes a little in spots, For the buttons (left and right, not the mousewheel which can act as a button as well), since it is so thin, there is not much travel on the button so it is more sensitive than I would like, just personal preference.

So all in all I like this mouse and would definitely recommend it with those caveats that if you're not expecting something super sturdy, and don't mind sensitive buttons then go for it!

product_title: TP-LINK Archer CR500 AC1200 Wireless Wi-Fi DOCSIS 3.0 16x4 Cable Modem Router, Certified for XFINITY by Comcast, Time Warner Cable, Charter
review_body:
The router I had previously lasted for 7 years. This router lasted for four months.

It worked fine initially, although the range was not fantastic. I occasionally had signal issues on the second floor of our house. Then, it just stopped working. I contacted customer service to see about getting a replacement router and was told I would be contacted within one business day with information on how to get a new router. Great, right? Nothing. My emails were met with excuses like "the team wasn't here yesterday" and being cc'd on a note to the "team" saying "please expedite this the customer is inconvenienced by not having internet at home." Because of the poor quality of the router and he terrible customer service, I would definitely stay away from any TP-Link products.

product_title: BenQ GL2760H 27-inch Full HD 1920 x 1080 2ms Response Time HDMI LED Monitor
review_headline: top quality monitor with a couple of very minor niggles
review_body:
I have been using this monitor for about 5 months and love it. The picture is clear, the colors are bright, the resolution upgrade from 1080p to 1440p is much more dramatic than I had expected, there are zero dead pixels and the stand allows for a wide range of positions. It has 1 HDMI, 1 DP, 1 DVI and 1 DSub (which, if you are buying a 1440p monitor, is useless unless you are using all the other ports for something else). The sound from the speakers isn't particularly good, but I use the headphone socket in the monitor to allow all my devices to output the sound to my headphones without having to change where I plug my headphones into. I don't get surround sound that way, but I use my regular TV setup for that purpose.

My only slight complaints are: 1) the inputs are somewhat difficult to access so if you are planning to swap HDMI cables a lot (such as between a playstation, blu-ray and a laptop), this may get annoying (I don't so it's not a big problem for me), and 2) the on-screen menu is not the easiest to navigate since having the buttons behind sometimes makes it hard to align which button you are pressing with the screen prompts. Several times I have pressed the wrong button and had to exit the menu and try again. However, the superb quality of this product far outweighs these minor complaints so I am still giving this monitor a 5/5 rating.

The price is fantastic for the quality - probably the best value for money in this category.

product_title: Intuos 3 4x5 PTZ430 Tablet Only with Software Bundle
review_headline: Nearly perfect tablet for any artist that is new to digital art, or artist on the go.
review_body: I've used this model of intuos tablet for about 4 years now, and it has served me well. It is the smallest size, but because I take it with me when I go on trips, it is perfect for my needs. The command keys always work perfectly and it recognizes my pen pressure very well. My only complaint is that if you're like me and take it with you, be careful of how you fold up the wires. The wires can become loose and refuse to work anymore (only an issue if you don't have it in one designated area all the time, so those of you who would have it at a desk or only move it once in a while should not experience this issue). This is my 3rd Intuos 3 since I started using them because of this issue. Luckily I'm very fortunate to never have had any problems with the pen, so I'm able to find sellers like this one who sell them inexpensively for the tablet and software only. For anyone who may be wary of the low cost and think there must me something wrong with them, I can assure there is not. I received mine today and have been drawing with it almost constantly since then. It works perfectly and because I already had the software installed, it remembered my keystrokes. I highly recommend this tablet to anyone who may be looking their first tablet as it is extremely easy to learn the maneuvers and customize to fit your art needs.

product_title: Silicon Power USB 3.0 J06 Jewel Flash Drive
review_headline: Good for compact size, not so great for speeds when compared to other drives
review_body:
The appeal for the purchase of this unit was for its COMPACT size, making it extremely easy to fit anywhere and carry around.
Also the fact that its so small it won't invade nearby usb ports in a desktop or laptop which some thicker usb drives tend to do.

The speeds are not up to par with similar or cheaper priced drives that supposedly offer same speeds.
The speeds this drive has using usb 2.0 are as follows:
7.8 mbs Write and 31.5 mbs write
Using it via usb 2.0 wouldn't classify it as ''class 10'' if comparing to sd cards its mediocre at best and its 3.0 writing speeds are not amazing either.

Using usb 3.0 speeds are as follows:
Write: 14.8 mbs Read: 74.7

So as you can see using usb 3.0 double if not more in speed.
The read speeds via usb 3.0 are actually great however the write speeds via usb 2.0 or usb 3.0 are just mediocre at best.

If you need an ''ok'' write speed small little drive this is definitely a good buy. However if you need something faster to write files you should probably buy something else. Id imagine most people would not be constatnly writing files to this drive so its usage and size is a value buy.

I actually wanted to try the 64 gb ( 3.0) version but it seems its never in stock. If silicon power ever releases a larger storage usb 3.0 and faster write speeds then its definitely an instant buy for me.

product_title: AMD Radeon HD 7950 3GB GDDR5 for Apple MAC Pro PCIe x16 Mini-DisplayPort HDMI DVI GPU Graphics Video Card 4K & 5K Resolution Support
review_body: Great card and great improvement to my mac pro 5,1 OS 10.9.5 40GB Ram The card was a plug and play, it's just a tiny bit (about 1mm) thicker than the original card, so I had to swap a PCI card with an ssd drive and move it up one slot, other than that no other issue. I can still use the port just above the card with an esata card. I didn't need to use the cables that came with the card as those already in my machine worked perfectly (My card already has 2 power cables) Computer boots no problem, boot screen on all mini-DP ports (not tested on other ports). I tested this card with 2k arriraw footage (via arriraw converter), 2k DPX 10bit Log C footage (from arriraw converter) in After effects (project at 24fps, 32bit/channel float). So far stable and excellent boost in preview and render on AE timeline compared to original card. Also fast conversion with MPG Streamclip from 2K animation to 2k Prores. Running 2 displays (27 Apple cinema display and Acer 272HUL) via miniDP connectors, I get 2560x1440 on both monitors simultaneously (check pictures) The seller was great card arrived in just few days. I'll update this in case something changes. Enjoy your renders :)

product_title: Keyma 3pcs/set Portable Electronic Accessories Hdd Travel Organizer Case Multi-functional Digital Storage Bag
review_headline: Handy bags to have around. Good for electronics like advertised, but also work for a ton of other uses.
review_body:
I love organizational products. This set of organizing bags is really handy. A few months ago I got a single medium one and I love it so much that I was thrilled to get a few more. Here’s what I love about them:

• Sizes: This size assortment is perfect. I can fit a wide variety of items in them. I like taking my other one on car trips for things to keep the kids busy, so this assortment gives me some options.
• Versatile: The inner removable, soft dividers make these bags work for so many things. I have used my bag for my nail stuff, electronics and car rides. Each time I can move the dividers to where it makes sense. There are tons of things you can do with them, even though they are marketed as electronics organizers.
• Quality: These are made well. The zippers are smooth and never catch, the seams are all nice. I haven’t found any flaws at all. There’s plenty of protection. The medium one fits our 7” tablet perfectly and has plenty of padding to keep it safe from bumps and drops.

I love these bags and am finding tons of ways to use them. The sizes are great and the versatility is handy for our family of four. I highly recommend if you’re in the market for this type of organizer. I was sent this to test and review. That has no bearing on my rating or review of the product, this is my honest opinion.

I love the calming blue waves. In terms of quality, I wouldn't say it's the best of the best, but it's perfect given the low cost of the product. For those who still want their apple logo visible, the logo still shines through the case. This case stays put and doesn't slide off or come loose at all. There are grooves that snap in holding it in place and they do their job very well. This case doesn't obstruct any plugs or jacks and doesn't need to be altered to listen to headphones or be charged. I don't know why I never got a case sooner, because I've always been concerned with getting scratches or marks on my laptop, but now I know I don't need to worry about that since this case is durable enough to protect against light bumps and scratches. I also don't have to be as concerned about spills. Overall I'm very happy I got this case and I think that it adds some character as well as protection to my laptop.

product_title: HP 15.6 Inch Laptop with Genuine 64-bit Windows 7 Home Premium, Quad-Core A8-6410 2.0GHz, 4GB RAM, 750GB HDD (Certified Refurbished)
review_headline: HP 15.6 Inch Laptop with Genuine 64-bit Windows 7 Home Premium, Quad-Core A8-6410 2.0GHz, 4GB RAM, 750GB HDD (Certified Refurbis
review_body:
It worked right out of the box. No missing parts or visible damage. It came on time as promised. It immediately recognized my WiFi network and connected without issues. Other than the huge windows updates that came after initiation, it worked OK right away. I primarily purchased this laptop because it still has the windows 7 operating system and the relatively fast four core AMD processor. It could be a really nice laptop, but HP fell short on this one!

The reason for the three stars is two fold. 1- Although the description clearly states that it has a USB3 port, it does not! 2- It is agonizingly slow. I would have returned it primarily for reason #1, but I really needed it for work and could not wait for the return and replacement delays.

On the positive side, it has a nice keyboard, well functioning track pad and a nice display when you look at it straight on. It has very little tolerance for off angle viewing.

It claims that there is a user replaceable RAM slot. But I don't dare open the back because it does not have a separate opening for access to RAM and the hard drive. Adding a second RAM and updating the HDD to an SSD would probably make this a more usable laptop.

Bernie

He didn't want some cheap keyboard because all his friends were getting another brand.  But I forced him to try it.  Now he really likes it.  It allows the screen to be in many more positions, and at many more angles.  The keyboard has a slightly better feel, and the case is more durable than he was expecting.  Plus this case allows the iPad to swivel and the other one didn't.  He had actually borrowed the other case/keyboard from a friend for a few days, so he was able to do a direct comparison.  Plus one really nice feature for him was, it takes two keys to shut the screen off.  The other on takes only one.  Other kids would walk by and, just for fun, turn off the screens of their friends. One problem with my monitor is it switches inputs when my computer shuts off the monitor (mine is set to turn off monitor 10 minutes after I quit using it). review_headline: I really love the device but...
review_body:
Might be suffering from early build quality issues. First one I picked up from Bestbuy had a dead pixel, returned that. Second I picked up had lighting issues at the bottom, they were uneven and really dark in some places, returned that. Third one I got, had a dead pixel, returned that. Fourth one I have now still has a dead pixel, but not going to keep trying.

Other than that, the device is fantastic. Great for reading outside, looks just like you are looking at any normal book. Reading inside is also pleasant with the use of the adjustable backlight. Device is very light, even with the official Kindle leather case on it. One thing I can't stand, and I wish manufacturers would stop doing, is the material. It is a fingerprint magnet. While I am glad it is not a glossy finish, the flat matte finish is not too much better.

It is not as bad since I have it in the case, but for us OCD people, it is a little annoying getting all dirty like that. Battery lasted for over a month with WIFI on, and still had some left, was not forced to charge, just chose to do so. UI is a little sluggish, but for what this device is that can be expected. Overall I am really happy with the device, would recommend to anyone looking to get into the e-ink game.

product_title: Kindle Fire HD 7 2014 Case, roocase Dual View 2014 Fire HD 7 Folio Case with Sleep / Wake Smart Cover with Multi-Viewing Stand for Amazon Kindle Fire HD 7 Tablet (4th Generation - 2014 Model), Black
review_headline: Great case for a great price!
review_body: Once I FINALLY got it, I love it! The shipping took 3 weeks, but that's for the seller's review. As far as this case goes, I am so tickled with it! Given the low price I was a little skeptical when I ordered it, thinking it would be some cheapo plastic-like material and the color would be weird, but those worries were all for nothing!   The case is beautiful and has a nice leather-type feel to it. The color is a gorgeous purple, not as bright-neon as the photo looks, which I'm glad for :). All the access points line up perfectly, and the velcro holds great. Also, the back of the case where the velcro sticks has not picked at all, and I've put it through the ringer these past 10 days (with a little help from my kitten)! Time will really tell, but I don't foresee any problems. It holds great on its side when I'm watching Netflix at night, and it holds great in the vertical position when I'm reading recipes as I cook. Well worth the wait!  Update-9/7/15: Another great quality of this case, it cleans up really easily! I've been teaching myself to make bread lately...what a mess! And, of course, I have to look at each recipe on my Kindle 10,000 times as I'm making it lol. This case has had butter, flour, wet dough, and some other things (that I'm now sure don't belong in bread) all over it, inside and out and it just wipes right off. The felt-like interior doesn't seem to absorb any of the goo I've thrown at it...I'm pleasantly surprised!

review_body:

Power supply slot on the bottom of the case is also definitely a huge plus because I find that it helps with cable management. Has 3 case fans and has room for additional case fans to be installed in it. Plenty of room for a long video card as well. Comes with HDD slide-out trays for easy installation.

My only complaint about the case is the space between the non-window side. If it was about 0.5-1.0 inches in between where the mobo rests and the side panel, it would fit, but with tucking away cables, it bulges the panel out. Other than that, it's an excellent case.

product_title: 2 Year CPS Consumer Priority Service Extended Warranty for Video Game Consoles Under $1,000.00
review_body: I have not had to file a claim on the warranty that came with my washer-dryer units (well, it didn't come with them, I bought the extended warranties). The booklet that came with my policy noticed spoke of replacing the unit(s) "free of charge" on multiple occasions, but the actual warranty document states that the maximum coverage is the original cost of the item. Therefore, if they spend money on a repair, and then the unit dies a year later, I will receive what I paid for the unit minus the cost of the repair they paid for -- and two years later the model(s) I bought may no longer be available and what is available may be more expensive. So, there is no "replacement at no charge." This is blatant dishonesty and I'm going to insist on getting the price of the extended warranties back from the appliance dealer. I am incredulous that in California, this kind of bait-and-switch tactic is allowed.

product_title: Amazon Kindle Fire HDX 7 Case, TechSpec(TM) Hot Pink 360 Rotating Case Cover Pouch Stand for Amazon Kindle Fire HDX 7
review_headline: It has a very clever rotating feature that allows for easy portrait and landscape viewing
review_body:
I have been using the Amazon Kindle Fire HDX 7 Case, TechSpec(TM) 360 Rotating Case Cover Pouch Stand for Amazon Kindle Fire HDX 7 for a month. It was exactly what I was looking for. It has a very clever rotating feature that allows for easy portrait and landscape viewing. It is supported by ridges on the cover in 2 different positions. One I find good for portrait and the other for landscape. On a flat surface they work just fine.
The cover folds back for easy hand held reading. It has an elastic band to keep it safely closed. Be aware that this is not a cover that turns your device off when you close it. The case is made of a comfortably soft front (kind of like velvet) and a more solid back. All openings are unobstructed.
I wanted to simply protect the screen of my Kindle and keep it safe during traveling without spending very much money, particularly because the devices usually outlast the cover. I cannot complain about the price of this cover.
I got exactly what I wanted. The price was more than fair. The only downside, and I am not taking a star off for it, is that it is a little “floppy” and I expect that the binding where it gets folded backward might be the first to go. But, in fact, I have just bought another one in pink as a spare. Pink makes it harder to lose and easier to find. The first one was black.
This cover feels so nice to hold and I would recommend this product.

product_title: Wacom Intuos Art Pen and Touch digital graphics, drawing & painting tablet
review_headline: Impression from a first time digital canvas user
review_body:
I never used a digital canvas before, so I had no idea what to expect. I always thought it would be tricky to setup, but actually this is one of the simplest devices. This is no more complicated than using a mouse. I plugged it in, installed the software, and I was able to move the cursor around Adobe Photoshop CS6 without any further setup. I didn't have to go into Photoshop menus, I was able to start drawing right away.

A simple pen tap on the digital canvas makes the brush tool start laying down its mark. The brush line gets thicker the harder I press down on the pen. At first I was playing around drawing some text, like my signature. What surprised me is how easy it is to use and how natural it feels. It's like writing on paper with a felt pen. Intuos Art responds accurately to slight differences in pressure to vary the thickness of the brush. So my signature looked just like it does on paper, on my first try!

If you are using a dual screen monitor, there is a setting in the Wacom Tablet Properties to assign one or both of the screens to the tablet surface (this confused me initially why Photoshop was only on the right side of the tablet, until I discovered this simple setting).

Since this digital canvas moves the cursor around, it's also a quick way to navigate the Photoshop menus. No need for a mouse.

I love this digital canvas - it's nice and small (doesn't create desk clutter), sleek looking, and the pressure sensing is very accurate.

(Important note - the very first Vine reviews were written before the product launched when the drivers were not available yet. Some people, including me, initially gave this a less than favorable review because drivers were not available yet, so the computer would not recognize the digital canvas. As soon as the product was publicly released on the market, we were able to download the software driver and actually use the Intuos Art canvas. You may come across some early reviews that talk about the product not working, but that's only because of a glitch with the timing of the previews samples and software driver release. Don't worry about reviews before the first week of September 2015, it works fine now.)t working, but that's only because of a glitch with the timing of the previews samples and software driver release. Don't worry about reviews before the first week of September 2015, it works fine now.)

product_title: TP Link AV500 Wi Fi Range Extender
review_headline: Works great, but wireless range isn't huge.
review_body:
I bought this because our house has tons of large mirrors in them and the router is in a back corner room. Unfortunately, that means that the only places that wi-fi works reliably are that room and the room directly above it. The other rooms are behind mirrors which essentially reflect wi-fi signals.

When I bought this, it allowed me to put one of the units in the room with the router, plug it into the wall, and plug an ethernet cable from the router to the device. I could put the other device anywhere else in the house and almost instantly have fast, wi-fi. It's a bit spottier than normal wifi so it can go out for a second or so every once in a while, but other than that it's excellent. The internet connection has low latency and high bandwidth.

One thing is that the range of the connection from this device isn't particularly huge if you want the low latency and high speed. If it's in the same room or the adjacent rooms, it offers excellent performance. It goes down significantly if you get much further than that.

Installation is dead simple. There is a little card that comes with it. It has a quick version of the instructions that allow you to have it up and running in a matter of a couple minutes. I definitely recommend the product.

product_title: Toshiba Satellite C55-C5241 15.6 Inch Laptop (Intel Core i5, 8 GB, 1TB HDD), Black
review_body:
This is one of the most difficult reviews I've had to write. I am so torn about whether I really like this laptop, or not. I've been using this Toshiba Satellite C55-C5241 for two weeks. Performance wise, I have had very few issues with it. When I first started using the laptop, it would freeze up, and I would have to reboot. Fortunately, that issue appears to have corrected itself, and is now operating perfectly.
The laptop is speedy, but as you would expect for the money, it is a basic model. My real complaints are with the keyboard, and housing. I've never had a laptop that came in a plastic housing; it's like playing with a Fisher Price toy. The keyboard is very soft, and the track pad is challenging. It's really hard to believe that this laptop will last for any length of time. But to be fair, considering the price point on this laptop, it has a lot going for it, and I have not seen anything that can equal it. So if your interested in a good, low cost, workhorse, this computer might fit the bill.

review_headline: Netgear Makes Stable, High Quality Products- Don't Be Afraid of Their Refurbs
review_body: After over twenty years in the IT business, I can tell you that I am totally comfortable buying and implementing Netgear refurbs. They are of high quality, very stable products.  I have a 1500+ square foot house of old school 60's construction that has high drop off after 25 ft or so, due to thick walls.  I bought two of these units to stabilize my connection throughout the house.  It took less than 10 minutes each to configure, and has been running stable since then (3 mos), no hiccups, no failure.  Mind you, as an IT director in the past, I would spend thousands on servers and switches (Cisco), only to have them fail after two days-one particular install had three failures in a row on the same install.  Netgear gives me good service.  Don't hesitate.  You need no special training, Just do it.  You won't be sorry.

review_body: I am a long time Apple user, I have loved them for the most part. I needed to replace my work at home laptop that died after 2 years. I loved the idea of a mobile laptop but never moved with it while working at home. I looked at all the specs and really finally realized I was being stupid. With this desktop I have all the speed and space I need to work at home and use it in my personal life. I also do some computer games and my old laptop was so slow, and of course non pc's aren't what you need at all. I have been so scared to go back to a pc but this computer is great. It is fast, it has a really good video card, there is always space to upgrade as needed and so far I love it. I have had it only a few days, got my Microsoft all up to date and have been getting to know it. But I love it so far. The speeds are something I am not used to, all the memory and ram space are unbelievable, its quiet, it looks great and I couldn't be happier. I checked other comparable computers elsewhere and found this one just as good, great price on Amazon and with Prime my overnight shipping was so cheap! I am happy and would recommend this for anyone like me; an at home user who does work and gaming on one computer.

product_title: Sentey micro usb metal cables
review_headline: The fanciest and highest quality charging cable I own.
review_body:
When it comes to charging cables for my android phones, I have tried to go with the cheap ones and ended up regretting it. Every cheap cable I've ever had, I've had major issues getting it to charge my phone. Usually the issue is that the wires inside the cables are not thick enough to carry electricity to the phone properly and the phone takes forever to charge, if it ever does at all. So now, even though I still consider myself a frugal person who tries to save money wherever possible, I now spend the little extra when I buy microUSB cables for our phones. I have found that they work so much better and more reliably, and also last much longer. This cable is no exception, in face it offers a level of quality that I have not yet seen in a charging cable.

The overall look of the cable is very appealing. The entire cable is red, with the ends being made mostly of metal and the cable itself being completely covered in braiding. The braiding makes the cable less likely to become tangled. There is a nice secure connection to the phone when it is plugged in and it seems to charge my phone a bit faster than even some of the other decent cables I have. Overall, I just really like the level of quality that went into creating this cable. I will be ordering more of these to replace my other aging charging cables.

I received this cable at a discount in exchange for my honest and unbiased review. All opinions are my own and no further compensation was provided.

review_headline: When I started pounding it with the stapler I knew we had a serious problem...
review_body:
When I started pounding it with the stapler I knew we had a serious problem...
After the return period expired it started scrolling down the page in several leaps, so that I had to wait until it reached the bottom and then scroll it up to the top again, wait again while it slowly scrolled itself to the bottom again in small leaps, scroll it back to the top again, wait again while it slowly scrolled itself to the bottom again in small leaps, scroll it back to the top again, wait again while it slowly scrolled itself to the bottom again in small leaps, scroll it back to the top again, wait again while it slowly scrolled itself to the bottom again in small leaps, scroll it back to the top again...
Finally. after repeating this 10-15 times (but sparing you, gentle reader, from reading all the iterations), and finding this to be an ongoing problem, I began to doubt my capabilities with a mouse and posted an Amazon question. Other people have had the same problem, and I missed those reviews. So if you find my review please take it seriously and DO NOT BUY if you don't want to risk damaging a perfectly good stapler on a nasty mouse.

product_title: Acer Aspire V15 Nitro Black Edition VN7-591G-70RT 15.6-Inch Full HD (1920 x 1080) Gaming Laptop
review_headline: Great deal for the price range - Buy an SSD for intensive work.
review_body:
I decided to write a quick review as I had been searching for a decent laptop at the $1000 price for quite some time before I decided to go with this one. So far after about 3 - 4 weeks of use the laptop has held up great. There have been very few issues with the WiFi as some people had been claiming (possibly caused by earlier iterations of the laptop itself / Network Adapter), the hard drive runs at a decent speed (however, I could imagine slower speeds for more intensive programs), and the build quality is very good. I would recommend installing or purchasing the laptop with an SSD if you're planning on using some intensive programs.

As soon as I purchased the laptop I simply removed all the bloatware from the computer and upgraded to Windows 10. There have been a couple instances of updating Windows leading to the system never wanting to completely restart, but aside from these couple of times it has performed well. As for the heat, I haven't checked the CPU / GPU temperatures under load, but the laptop itself never reaches a heat that I would find uncomfortable to the touch.

Overall, the laptop is a good deal for your money (I purchased the laptop for $900.00 during the back-to-school time frame, so I plan on adding an SSD soon with the saved money) that will perform well while *hopefully maintaining its reliability. Some small quirks - not sure if related to Windows 10 or not - provoked me to rate it 4-stars, but others may not have these issues. I will EDIT if I ever run into any additional problems.

product_title: ASUS Chromebook Touch
review_headline: This one is a WINNER of a Chromebook!
review_body:
I never write product reviews..., but this time I am. I LOVE this device. If you're on a Windows or Mac laptop, probably like me, you already know that it is a major PITA to configure your new computer. Program disks, going to websites to find new drivers, driver updates, finding installation keys, calling Adobe or Microsoft to convince them that you want to install some software yet again. Sigh.

With ChromeOS, almost no configuration necessary. Especially if you're already a heavy Chrome user and have Chrome set up "just right" on your Mac/PC. That configuration, as well as the extensions, auto-magically come over when you start up your Chromebook and sign in. And if, like me, you spend 95% of your time in Chrome anyhow, then you simply won't miss Windows or OS X.

As for the hardware, seriously, this thing looks like a mini-MacBook. Then I show my Mac-loving brethren the touch screen, as well as the tablet mode, and first thing they want to know is "how much" and "where did you buy it". This Chromebook will make your MacBook Air feel like a boat anchor, and the touchscreen/tablet mode will make others green with envy. Plus, this thing is seriously light, has a bright IPS display, will slip into a case made for large tablets, and runs for hours. If you're already bought into the Google/Chrome ecosystem, you'll love this device.

Buy the 4 GB RAM version, since 2 GB is a little light if you like having lots of tabs open. My only wish is that ASUS would sell the power adapter for the Flip, so that I can keep one in the office as well as at home.

product_title: Seal Shield SILVER SURF TOUCH "All-in-One" Multimedia Keyboard (87777S) Category: Standard Keyboards
review_body:
Let's start off with the one plus. Yes this keyboard can be washed. I've washed it in a dishwasher and I've submerged it completely in a sanitizing solution and it worked afterwards. That's the only positive thing I have to say about these keyboards though.

This product is the Supreme poster child for terrible design. I think the people who designed this never once sat down and actually used their product.

Where to start... the Home button is right next to the backspace button, so if you're used to a regular US keyboard layout then you're going to spend a lot of frustrating time getting used to the new layout, as the cursor moves where you don't want it to be and you erase perfectly good text. As if that weren't enough, they located the right trackpad button right where the heel of your right hand is when you use a natural hand position for typing. So if you use the \\"built in hand rest feature\\", your right hand will push the button and your cursor will move to wherever you have it pointed to, which is almost invariably not where you want to be typing. The trackpad itself is too small for any real use and you'll find yourself begging the heavens for a mouse.

And then there's the sticking keys. Out of the four keyboards that we tested, two of them have keys that stick down. One has a problem with the F1 button and another has a problem with the 4 key. Not only is it badly designed, it's also very badly made and I don't expect they would last very long under normal use. Not that I could bring myself to use one long enough to find out; its ability to resist the sudden deceleration of hitting a wall, or its ability to wistand the weight of a Freightliner truck, would get tested long before I ever washed it enough times to find out if it can withstand repeated washings.

popped back up. See what i mean? Just for the record this sentence ws typed usimng the keyboard in question. The key spacing is all rong, and the comma key juststuck in the down position,, and now it [

Maybe... MAYBE... if you work in the medical industry and type by pecking at the keys with two fingers... this might be worth your time and money... But if you're entertaining the idea of this as a work tool, one that has even the remotest link to the concept of productivity, you would do yourself and your company a great disservice by spending money on one of these.

product_title: Innogie Dual USB 10400mAh AlienPower Portable Charger Battery & External Battery Power Bank for for Smartphones & Tablets
review_headline: Great for all devices and to use anytime you cant charge your phone/tablet on the go!
review_body: I received this portable charger by innogie for a product review and it is really cool. We used this portable charger on a road trip and found it to be super useful. The kids (all teens) absolutely loved that the top looks just like an alien when it is all lit up. I really like that this can work with so many different devices. Half out our road trip participants had iPhone and the other half had android. We were all able to use this charger for our phones. Not only did we use it for our phones, but we also used it for a variety of tablets and electronic readers. It takes less than an hour to completely charge the portable charger and then takes between 30 and 40 minutes to charge phones or devices on it, depending on the battery life when you plug it in to charge. My daughter and her friend used the charger to charge their devices while they played on it and it only delayed the charging slightly, but it still charged. This is a great item to have on hand. I like to use it when I know that I will be out of the house/car for long periods of time. It was perfect for our hike in the woods and mountains on our vacation.

review_headline: Nice for a first mini itx build, or any first build
review_body:
I built a Hackintosh custom mini.

Gigabyte GA-H97N WiFi
Xeon E3-1231V3
Crucial 16gb ballistix sport
Samsung 250gb 750 evo
WD 2TB black HD
Corsair CS550M (semi-modular) PSU
EVGA nvidia 2gb 740 video card
This is a very easy case to work in. Both sides and the top come off exposing the entire frame. Easy to install the drives (tool-free!) And really really easy to install the MB. Don't know if I'm just getting better at installation or whether the whole compact build is just easier overall. Some of the struggles with cables I have had with larger cases just didn't happen this time. I didn't experience the extreme crunch with the PSU that we did with the corsair RM650 in the Graphite 380T, but then the CS550M is just smaller. The stock case fan is silent. Can't say the same for the stock Xeon CPU cooling fan... Will not be doing much beyond excel spreadsheets, openscad and iTunes/ripping CDs, so I don't expect any thermal surprises. Will update this review if anything changes.

product_title: Illuminated Living-Room Keyboard K830
review_headline: Exceptional range but is that because it uses more power?
review_body: It's one pricey wireless keyboard compared to the others all right.  The one thing it really impressed me with is the range.  With my previous keyboard sometimes I get dropouts or slow responses from the couch but this thing works perfectly.  The light is also very nice and works well.  My only gripe is you have to first press a key to turn it on so you have to choose some safe key to press.  I wish it worked like the Harmony One remote where when it detects movement it turns the lights on.  I'm happy with every aspect of it except one thing.  The battery doesn't last very long at all.  It lasts me about 3 weeks on one charge which is kind of crazy low.  I've had it for two months now and had to charge it three times after the initial charge.  My old keyboard with two AA batteries lasted 6 months and within a minute I could have it up and running with new batteries.  With this keyboard you have to plug it in to let it charge so it can be difficult or impossible to charge and use at the same time.  I even resorted to using one of those small battery banks so I can have the keyboard with me while it charged.  The only other con is it absorbs oil and fingerprints like a monster so if that sort of thing bothers you this may not be ideal.  The keyboard and keys have a matte finish that really shows off oil.  That doesn't bother me though but that battery thing does so four stars it is.

product_title: Elgato Game Capture HD, Xbox and PlayStation High Definition Game Recorder for Mac and PC
review_body:
Concatenated version:
It's awesome, records 1080p over HDMI at flawless framerates as well as high bitrate, manages source resolution changes in the middle of recording surprisingly well, good audio that's properly synchronized, and doesn't need any excessive cables to operate (low-profile). This is a very good product that is perfect for people who want to record gameplay or any HDMI device that doesn't have HDCP encryption (until Elgato decides to include an HDMI splitter in the recording device or the user has their own). It earns 5-stars as a recording/livestreaming device, not video editing software.

A lot more details:
The image quality is like the source (check included pic) and he recording bitrate is quite high relative to YouTube's recommendations. YouTube's recommended bitrates for 60 FPS are on the left and my recording results are on the right, also at 60 FPS.
360p: YT~1.5 Mbps | HD60~N/A
480p: YT~4 Mbps | HD60~11 Mbps
720p: YT~7.5 Mbps | HD60~20 Mbps
1080p: YT~12 Mbps | HD60~40 Mbps
1440p: YT~24 Mbps | HD60~N/A
2160p: YT~53-68 Mbps | HD60~N/A
You may need some more hard disk space if you decide to record in a higher bitrates/resolutions. Cool thing is that the bitrate is high enough that it would be worthwhile to upsample the video to a higher resolution if you're using YouTube to allow the video player to output the higher bitrate to improve video quality.
It should be mentioned that you can record interlaced (I tried 1080i), but only at 30 FPS. It is strongly apparent that the HD60 automatically deinterlaces the video (based off of the output video properties which was set to export at MP4). Major pluses for that.

Audio is recorded at around 224 Kbps, with 2 channels (stereo), and with a sampling rate of 48 KHz through HDMI (I was unable to test the 3.5mm jack). Nothing fancy, simple, and sweet. It also allows you to record commentary and audio from HDMI/3.5mm source independently so you can control/modify it in post-production if need be (as long as you don't edit with the built-in software).

Livestreaming is extremely computer intensive and your system should be up to par with the mandated specs if you want to, but if your computer can handle it, it's impeccable. Audio control for both game and commentary is astonishing with simple "knobs" with db levels next to them as well as audio monitors. The software is well set up for uploading directly to YouTube and streaming by allowing information for the game you're playing, what level you're on, the title of the video/stream, and the description as well as doing simple tasks like cutting the video and placing it where it needs to be. It's sufficient for say a new YouTube user, but someone more professional or one that yearns for higher quality and options for editing may want better software that can import images and control audio levels post-recording.

Lights on the top of the HD60 indicate what is being transmitted to the device and what's happening if you're familiar. I did not have to use it and it tends to be out of sight, but it's helpful if you need to troubleshoot the product for whatever reason or for alerts for if something happens in the software that was unexpected and you can't view it while recording.

Wait 20 seconds before turning it back on. If it helps you, find this post useful. This needs more attention.

The product itself is worth five stars but if the new software update makes the keyboard useless, then you can barely use your kindle the way it's meant to be used and that's a big deal. Even a brand new car with a shot out motor is only worth a few hundred bucks. I wanted to rate this higher, but I can't.

Included $25 gift card for the Windows Store from Microsoft however, Microsoft then emails you several times to let you know if you do not use your gift card within the first eight weeks after you register for Office 365, they remove from your Windows Store account the balance of the gift card. The minimum amount for the maintenance on the HP Stream 13 Laptop for one year is $149. There is only 2GB memory, one app from the Windows Store and you are then out of disk space. Microsoft customer support team suggests you purchase he external hard drive for $119 plus tax. T-mobile free 4G data for life except you can only use that for 200MB each month, so make sure there are no other programs running at the time you might need to use your free 200MB broad band connection. review_headline: Feels a little cheap, but it's a good value and fits very well
review_body: I wanted an inexpensive cover for this tablet, and this one fits that need well.  This cover is very reasonably priced and the design is good - very functional.  Material quality is decent - it will probably hold up pretty well - and build-quality (stitching and cuts) are quite nice for the price.  The material is not extremely soft.  It feels a little cheap, but then it IS a very inexpensive cover - so I won't deduct a star for that.  My only deduction is because it isn't available in a tan or brown color.  Also, my cover was shipped in a thin, soft mailer and was deformed (bowed), with bent corners when it arrived.  I believe this will be okay with time, as the case was not actually damaged (otherwise I would have filed a claim).  It will just take time to regain its original, flat shape.  For the vendor, I would just suggest shipping these in a more rigid container.  Overall, this case is a good value and it fits the tablet very well.

review_body:

My internet speeds were varying wildly between 0.4 and 35 Mbps, even though I am supposed to be getting 75 Mbps. Plugging my patch cord directly into the modem revealed that the router was to blame.
Setup was super easy and I am now reliably getting 90 Mbps, so it's all good!

product_title: Samsung 850 EVO Parent
review_body: Installed on a 2012 MacBook Pro. Reduced my boot to desktop speed from 30 seconds to 10 seconds. Noticeably faster for all applications. It also shuts off nearly instantly now versus several seconds. Everything is much speedier. And the intangible rewards are it's totally silent, so no more whirring spindle HD cranking up like an antiquated steam engine. It also makes my laptop run cooler (no moving parts) and battery life is improved. Installation was a snap even though I had never installed an SSD before. There are plenty of YouTube videos giving step-by-step instructions. If you're on the fence about getting an SSD, don't hesitate. It's totally worth the money. The only downside is once you have it installed, you'll regret not having done it sooner. I have lots of Samsung products and I feel like their build quality overall is good as a company. Have not had any issues in the several months I've been using it, so I can't speak to technical support insights.

product_title: Kuzy - Plastic Case for Older MacBook Pro 13.3" (Model: A1278) Aluminum Unibody Ultra Slim Rubberized Matte Cover
review_headline: Eight months in and not holding up well
review_body:
I've had this case for about eight months now and I have to say, I'm not terribly impressed. I'd like to start by saying that I'm not hard on my computer. I never travel long distance with it and it rarely, if ever, leaves my house. A few weeks in to my use two of the little pads on the bottom half of the case, the ones that keep the computer from scratching the surface beneath it, popped off. I was able to superglue them back on and thus far they've held. A month in one of the clips that keeps the bottom case attached completely broke off. Now I have to fight to keep the bottom case on and it's constantly collecting crumbs and other nastiness between the case and my computer. I don't even eat over my laptop, so yeah, gross. I also dinged one corner of the top case when I was moving it from my desk, creating a little crack in the plastic, which has since spread and even chipped off an entire chunk of the case. Nothing like putting duct tape on your computer.

To be honest, I think this case is exactly the same as the cases you see here on Amazon for ten or twelve dollars. My mom purchased a case for half the price of the Kuzy and it looks identical (minus the Kuzy logo). I'd hoped that with the slightly steeper price this would have equated to a slightly better quality case, but mine is practically coming apart and my mother's is still in decent condition. In fairness I think the case has done its job at protecting my computer. I can't verify that, though, because I'm pretty sure if I take the case off now it will fall apart.

To sum up: if you want a temporary cheap case, buy a cheaper one than this, because honestly it's exactly the same and not worth the extra eight or ten bucks.

product_title: 2 TB Memory USB Flash Drive with Keychain and protective cover + FREE Mystery Gift !
review_headline: Looking for a drive that will destroy your data? You have come to the right place.
review_body:
If it seems too good to be true - it usually is!

*Nobody* currently makes true 2TB USB flash drives. You risk losing some or all of your valuable data if you buy this drive. Read on...

Beware fake capacity flash drives - especially unusually low-priced generic (and brand-name look-alike) drives 64GB and up.

This and many other cheap apparently high capacity flash drives are really low capacity 4GB or 8GB drives that have been hacked (controller chip settings altered) by dishonest Chinese suppliers so that they show a false inflated capacity. That is why their price is so low. Such drives are then redistributed by a few clueless resellers and by many other fully-aware resellers who are out to make a quick profit.

These drives will show their false capacity in Windows properties, but will quietly lose or corrupt your valuable data once their true capacity is exceeded. They will seem to work at first and files will look okay in their folders, but you will eventually find some or all of your data corrupt when played, viewed, or otherwise read back. Your valuable data will be irretrievably lost.

As of Q3 2015, *nobody* makes true 2TB USB flash drives (but teh market is full of fakes). The top available USB flash drive capacity is 1TB with the Kingston DTHXP30 HyperX Predator drive. To achieve that capacity, Kingston mounts 8 memory chips, a controller chip and other necessary components on three interconnected circuit cards packed into a necessarily bulky package. Search for "DTHXP30 review" to see photos of the internals. Those drives cost several hundred dollars, and the lion's share of this cost is the memory chips themselves. The circuit card, case, assembly costs, packaging, and distribution only add a few dollars.

The Chinese are great at producing a wide range of interesting generic and novelty designs, but they don't have a magic supply of cheap memory chips. They also do not have the ability to make a 2TB drive using a single chip design as is contained in this drive. The technology is not there yet.

There are lots of good flash drives available on Amazon, but only a few with true capacities above 256GB - all brand name drives costing several hundred dollars each. True capacity generic drives top out at 128GB for USB 2.0 drives (costing about $40), and the less common 256GB USB 3.0 generics (costing about $90). The market is also flooded with fake capacity drives offered at prices well below the true capacity drives.

Be especially cautious of sellers that offer the same style in multiple sizes, but where each doubling in size is only 25% to 50% more than the size below. For example, if the 64GB drive is only $5 more than the 32GB drive, or where the 128GB drive is only $10 more than the 64GB. Real memory is not that cheap.

If you do buy a low-priced drive, the first thing you should do is test the capacity using a utility called h2testw. This will fill the drive with data and then verify that it can be read back intact. The write phase usually completes without error. It is the verify phase that exposes the fake capacity. Testing the first 32GB is usually sufficient. For reasons stated above, you cannot trust the capacity displayed in Windows properties.

You can also test by filling the drive up to at least 35GB with videos or other large media files and then *most importantly* check to see if they can be played back. If the capacity is faked, the first few will play, but past some point, the rest will be corrupt.

Do not trust the capacity or space remaining shown in the properties display - that is exactly what is faked.

Search for "fake capacity flash" using your favorite search engine for more information.ility to make a 2TB drive using a single chip design as is contained in this drive. The technology is not there yet.

There are lots of good flash drives available on Amazon, but only a few with true capacities above 256GB - all brand name drives costing several hundred dollars each. True capacity generic drives top out at 128GB for USB 2.0 drives (costing about $40), and the less common 256GB USB 3.0 generics (costing about $90). The market is also flooded with fake capacity drives offered at prices well below the true capacity drives.

For example, if the 64GB drive is only $5 more than the 32GB drive, or where the 128GB drive is only $10 more than the 64GB. Real memory is not that cheap.

If you do buy a low-priced drive, the first thing you should do is test the capacity using a utility called h2testw. This will fill the drive with data and then verify that it can be read back intact. The write phase usually completes without error. It is the verify phase that exposes the fake capacity. Testing the first 32GB is usually sufficient. For reasons stated above, you cannot trust the capacity displayed in Windows properties.

You can also test by filling the drive up to at least 35GB with videos or other large media files and then *most importantly* check to see if they can be played back. If the capacity is faked, the first few will play, but past some point, the rest will be corrupt.

Do not trust the capacity or space remaining shown in the properties display - that is exactly what is faked.

Search for "fake capacity flash" using your favorite search engine for more information.

product_title: ASUS X551 15.6-inch Laptop (Intel Celeron 2.16GHz Processor, 4GB RAM, 500GB HDD, Windows 8.1 includes Windows 10 upgrade), Black
review_headline: The computer is just OK, customer support is GREAT!
review_body: I bought this laptop (Asus calls it a notebook), because I needed a device that had USB ports so I could program remote controls in the field. The USB ports failed after 4 months. I called Asus support, who by the way are excellent, and tried about five different things including reinstalling the BOIS. Nothing worked so on my 3rd. call to them they suggested a total system reset and assured me that would fix the problem. It didn't. So now I guess I will be sending it back to get a replacement. Asus support is EXCELLENT. It's not their fault the computer is defective. I'm certain I will be able to get a new computer because when I purchased it through Amazon.com it came with a 1 year guarantee against fire, water, dropping, or any other mishap that might happen, plus it's still in warranty. One thing I hate about this computer other than Windows 8.1 is you have to hold down the function key and volume up/down to adjust the volume. Really? Two fingers to adjust the volume? Plus these keys are on opposite ends of the keyboard, a really poor design. The battery life seemed to shorten considerably since I purchased it. At first it lasted about 7 hours, 10.5 months later I only get about 3 hours out of it. All in all it's about what I expected from a $200 computer. If you just need a basic computer it's not bad.

product_title: Microsoft Arc Touch Bluetooth Mouse
review_headline: Middle button too sensitive. Hard to connect to Bluetooth. Limited customization options.
review_body:
The middle button is extremely sensitive. I have mine set to bring up the Start Menu on a double tap, and every bump with my middle finger seems to activate it. It also took me more than twenty minutes to get it to go into pairing mode. The bottom button is extremely difficult to work with, and the "light" that shows it's in pairing mode actually comes on AFTER pairing mode is activated, not AS pairing mode is activated. (In other words, by waiting for the light, I was holding the button on too long, and the mouse was power cycling off.)

Kind of annoying that a mouse manufactured by Microsoft IS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH THE MICROSOFT MOUSE AND KEYBOARD CENTER! Seriously, you can't make your own products work together? In order to customize it, you have to download an APP from the Microsoft store. So far, the app ONLY allows you to customize the middle button and scrolling rates/feedback volume. I expected, for a mouse that retails for $64, to be able to set a two or three button click as well.

I like that it seems to have less lag than the cheaper Optimal Shop one on my Win10 tablet. It also loses connection less frequently. I like that it flattens out, but the sensitivity of the middle button remains a concern. Hopefully I'll get used to it, or Microsoft will recognize that maybe their products should work together and allow the Keyboard and Mouse center to work with it.

review_body: I purchased this enclosure to build an external drive for my Xbox one. The features are pretty great for the price,  Usb 3.0 and can utilize up to a 4tb drive. I used the included instructions to attach the drive and build the enclosure,  it only took a couple min.  Before I knew it,  I was plugging it in to the back of my Xbox one and let the Xbox do its thing.  All in all this is one of the few enclosures out there that had everything I needed to build a 3.5" external drive for an Xbox one and is a solid choice for those looking to do the same.

product_title: StarTech.com Cat 6 RJ45 Modular Plug for Solid Wire  (CRJ45C6SOL50)
review_headline: Prepare to lose your mind at first if you've never done this before
review_body:
OK here's my take on fabricating Ethernet cables using these connectors. I have basically spent my entire adult life fabricating, repairing and installing cables of all types. It's a fact that some cables are a cinch to make and others will make you want to tear your hair out. The trick of course is understanding the technique. Easy to say, hard to do sometimes. Instead of reprinting a step-by-step instruction , here are a few tips for those who want to try this.

1) After you comb the wire out and order the colors according to the standard you need, cut them all on a diagonal. This will make it easy to insert the wires in the loading bar in the correct order.
2) Pay attention to the loading bar (read the review titled "INSTRUCTIONS!!!" for more info on this
3) Check colors one more time and push loading bar down the wire
4) Insert into connector and crimp
5) Test with Ethernet cable tester (dirt cheap here on Amazon)

All said and done it is a tedious process at first but like anything else it gets easier as you get more experience. Prepare to waste a few (dozen) connectors while you are learning the technique.

product_title: 2 TB USB FLASH DRIVE, HP USB Flash Drive 2 Tb Metal USB Flash Drive Silver Color USB Stick Boxed+ FREE MYSTERY GIFT
review_headline: HP? Not! 2TB? Not! Nothing good awaits you here. This drive is both counterfeit *AND* fake-capacity.
review_body:
FACT: *Nobody* currently makes true 2TB USB flash drives.

The photos show an apparent HP v250w USB Flash Drive, but it is a fake. Genuine HP v250w drives (altually manufactured by PNY) are made to a maximum capacity of 128GB. See "http://www.pny.com.tw/index.php?mode=product_detail&PID=78" for HP v250w product specifications and check for yourself. Any v250w advertised with a higher capacity is one of many Chinese-made counterfeits that have flooded the market.

On top of that, counterfeit drives invariably also have fake capacity. That is why their price is so low. Read on...

You risk losing some or all of your valuable data if you buy this drive. Read on...

Beware fake capacity flash drives - especially unusually low-priced generic (and brand-name look-alike) drives 64GB and up.

This and many other cheap apparently high capacity flash drives are really low capacity 4GB or 8GB drives that have been hacked (controller chip settings altered) by dishonest Chinese suppliers so that they show a false inflated capacity. That is why their price is so low. Such drives are then redistributed by a few clueless resellers and by many other fully-aware resellers who are out to make a quick profit.

These drives will show their false capacity in Windows properties, but will quietly lose or corrupt your valuable data once their true capacity is exceeded. They will seem to work at first and files will look okay in their folders, but you will eventually find some or all of your data corrupt when played, viewed, or otherwise read back. Your valuable data will be irretrievably lost.

As of Q3 2015, *nobody* makes true 2TB USB flash drives (but teh market is full of fakes). The top available USB flash drive capacity is 1TB with the Kingston DTHXP30 HyperX Predator drive. To achieve that capacity, Kingston mounts 8 memory chips, a controller chip and other necessary components on three interconnected circuit cards packed into a necessarily bulky package. Search for "DTHXP30 review" to see photos of the internals. Those drives cost several hundred dollars, and the lion's share of this cost is the memory chips themselves. The circuit card, case, assembly costs, packaging, and distribution only add a few dollars.

The Chinese are great at producing a wide range of interesting generic and novelty designs, but they don't have a magic supply of cheap memory chips. They also do not have the ability to make a 2TB drive using a single chip design as is contained in this drive. The technology is not there yet.

There are lots of good flash drives available on Amazon, but only a few with true capacities above 256GB - all brand name drives costing several hundred dollars each. True capacity generic drives top out at 128GB for USB 2.0 drives (costing about $40), and the less common 256GB USB 3.0 generics (costing about $90). The market is also flooded with fake capacity drives offered at prices well below the true capacity drives.

If you do buy a low-priced drive, the first thing you should do is test the capacity using a utility called h2testw. This will fill the drive with data and then verify that it can be read back intact. The write phase usually completes without error. It is the verify phase that exposes the fake capacity. Testing the first 32GB is usually sufficient. For reasons stated above, you cannot trust the capacity displayed in Windows properties.

You can also test by filling the drive up to at least 35GB with videos or other large media files and then *most importantly* check to see if they can be played back. If the capacity is faked, the first few will play, but past some point, the rest will be corrupt.

Do not trust the capacity or space remaining shown in the properties display - that is exactly what is faked.

Search for "fake capacity flash" using your favorite search engine formore information.more information.

product_title: Anker Dual Display Universal Docking Station with DVI/HDMI (up to 2048 x 1152)
review_headline: I was disappointed to find that my HP laptop had no provision ...
review_body:
I recently replaced my work desktop with a laptop for portability. I quickly realized that I missed using a standard full-size keyboard and mouse and larger monitor. I was disappointed to find that my HP laptop had no provision for a docking station. During my search I came across this Anker Universal Docking station that uses a computer's USB 3.0 port to replicate ports normally found in a docking station. I was skeptical of this concept because I didn't think USB would provide enough bandwidth for up to two high resolution displays, ethernet, 6 other USB ports and audio. I gave it a shot only because of the reliability and quality of other Anker products I had purchased in the past.

Long story short, it has delivered on every promise. My expectations have been surpassed. The product does what they say it will do, it looks good and it was packaged professionally. I am surprised that the computer recognizes all the peripherals connected to it as easily as it would recognize any individual USB device. My laptop happily runs with or without the docking station attached. It makes the transition from dual to single and back to dual displays flawlessly and even jumps between wired ethernet and WIFI automatically. Incidentally, I am running 64-bit Windows 8.1.

I strongly recommend this device and am considering purchasing a second one for home use.

product_title: Kindle Paperwhite 3G, 6" High Resolution Display with Built-in Light, Free 3G + Wi-Fi [Previous Generation]
review_headline: Love my Kindle Paperwhite but battery life is exaggerated
review_body:
I love my Kindle Paperwhite! It delivers on all promises except battery life.

CONS
**I don't get weeks or days of battery with one charge, but I get what I really want: I can read all day, and charge at night. When not in use, I get about two weeks, not "several" weeks or months. This is probably my 3rd or 4th kindle device, and I have never gotten even close to the claimed battery life.
**No color. I don't know if color is possible on the "paperweight" screen style, but it would be awesome if they manage it.
**No audio. I have an extensive Audible audiobook library, which is available for use on non-paperwhite devices, but not on this one.

PROS
Just about everything you could want in an e-reader:
*Non-glare, backlit screen for indoor, outdoor, poolside... anywhere.
*Adjustable fonts and text size.
*I can read for hours without eyestrain or fatigue. The screen is very easy on the eyes!
*PORTABILITY!!!! I have over 1,000 books on my Kindle. Easy for traveling with a huge library in a unit smaller and lighter than ONE PAPERBACK!

I LOVE MY KINDLE PPERWHITE!!

review_headline: Three Months in and it Sucks Hardcore
review_body:
When I first got this router it worked flawlessly. It has been three months and now the wireless connection is the most frustrating connection I've dealt with in my life. If I restart the router it works fine for about five minutes, and after that it regularly pings greater than 500ms locally. It is not a connection issue by my devices as several devices in my home all have horrible ping to this router. inSSIDer shows that the signal is strong and isn't dropping so it must be something with the actual routing and not the wireless connection itself.

It makes basic wireless internet browsing a horrendous experience, let alone online gaming which is half of what I purchased this router for.

review_headline: Big fan of this fan. I guess you could say I'm a fanboi now.
review_body:
This fan is awesome. Super high quality. I am not a huge fan of the color scheme, but the performance is top notch. The included extension cable, splitter and low power adapter look great and are a nice included accessory.

I used this fan to replace one of the stock Corsair fans on my H75 AIO cooler. I have it in the top of my Silverstone FT-02 case, with a Silverstone AP-120 fan pulling and this fan in the push position. It is near silent at 1500rpm. Not only is it about half as quiet as the stock Corsair fan, it also lowered the temps at idle by about 3°C.

Well worth the money.
