product_title: Corsair Mechanical Gaming Keyboard
review_body:
The Corsair STRAFE is great for my FPS gaming ways. The STRAFE delivers on a few fronts: style, a deep program to customize keys and profiles, great mechanical feel, and quality of build.

The contour keys and the blood red LEDs will get your inner Austin Powers to say "I'm dead sexy." The keys pop out of the keyboard platform like a lift kit on a pickup truck. It is quite the visual. Two LED bars on the rears of the keyboard gives it a nice touch, bold and stylin'.

What I like most about the STRAFE is the mechanical feedback. The touch is effortless. A soft touch will press the key. You can "strafe" all day in CSGO with these keys without tiring. When I'm browsing the web and I have my left hand on the WASD keys by habit, I find myself hitting a bunch of "sssssssssss" because it is so sensitive. I love FPS gaming with this keyboard as well as typing with it. If you're a fast typist and not accommodated to the mechanical "lifted" keys, there may be an adjustment period in which you would curl your fingers a bit more to be able to reach the entire letter keyboard. At work my keyboard is low profile so I tend to lay my fingers a bit flatter. The STRAFE won't really allow that if you're typing.

The Corsair software is quite deep. Visit the Corsair website or do a google search. Not difficult to find. The included software includes the ability to check and install firmware updates, change the color profile (pulse, rain, bold), program keystrokes, macros, and change the LED mode.

Build quality is top notch - the platform the keys sit on is sturdy, bulky, and doesn't feel hollow. The USB cable is ridiculous thick - 4 Gauge I am estimating. The USB head comes with two well protected usb connections, both of which are required to power this beast. Make sure you have enough spare USB ports. There is also an extra USB port to power your headset, charge devices, etc. It's great for cable management and desktop convenience.

I believe the STRAFE is perfect for FPS gamers - no G1 - G20 extra macro keys you'd use for MMOs. If you don't mind not having the wrist rest and different colored LEDS, the STRAFE is an excellent mechanical keyboard choice.desktop convenience.

I believe the STRAFE is perfect for FPS gamers - no G1 - G20 extra macro keys you'd use for MMOs. If you don't mind not having the wrist rest and different colored LEDS, the STRAFE is an excellent mechanical keyboard choice.

product_title: Corsair Gaming  Dolby 7.1 USB Gaming Headset
review_headline: Great Headset, Price to Value, and Customer service!
review_body: Great gaming headset! Comfort is 10/10. Sound Quality whether listening to music or playing a game 10/10. Price to Worth 20/10. There is some debate whether surround sound is worth it and for this headset it is especially if you play fps games you can clearly tell if someone is behind you or behind you to the right or around the corner. Corsair as a company is great I have 2 headsets with them and both of them broke at one point (not do to faulty material but do to an accident) and the replaced them with the newest version. This is why I do business with corsair first if I can and if I don't like the option I have through them (which hasn't happened yet) I will go spend my money at another company. I have had both headsets for over a year now I believe and the sound quality is the same as when I first got them. Another thing which depending on the situation is a pro or a con, these headphones can double as speakers if you turn them up all the way and set them down you can hear them clear across the house, that doesn't sound like a huge but that is the pro side when you want them on your head you are left with a small amount of wiggle room for adjusting the volume in volume mixer. What is weird though is that the wireless counterpart does not have this feature/issue. A small con worth saying I am a female gamer and this headset occasionally falls off my head at the smallest size it adjusts to was built for a man sized head.

product_title: S-ZONE Fashion Canvas Genuine Leather Trim Travel Briefcase 15.6-inch Laptop Bag (Big)
review_body:
I was in the market for a new computer bag that could hold a decent amount of peripherals (books, cords, tablets) as well as my HP Chormebook. Planned on going out of the country in a few months and I wanted something that was nicer than the cheap computer case you can buy at best buy for $20, that had a little style, and could fit a that was 14 ish inches from one side to the other. If it had prime shipping, even better, because I wanted to get a good feel for it before my trip.

The shipment arrived on time, and from everything I've seen so far, the bag is as advertise. The adjustable strap is easy to use, the pockets are deep enough for a variety of items. I'm a nerd, and i used the bag over the past week to go out gaming - carried notebooks, said laptop, tablet, and a bunch of heavy hard back gaming books and dice, with no issues at all. IT could just as easily carry a text book or two for a class.

In short, if you are looking for a sturdy, well built, stylish laptop bag, that can fit a 13-15 inch wide laptop, then this is the bag for you.

product_title: Alldaymall A10X Quad Core 10 inch tablet Android 4.4.2 KitKat, 1GB RAM, 16GB Nand Flash, Built-in Bluetooth, Dual Camera, 3D Game Supported
review_headline: The good and the bad of the A10X
review_body:
I've owned a number of tablets over the years. Most recently the 2012 version of the Nexus 7. I decided I wanted to go back to the larger 10.1" size, but wanted to keep the cost low. After looking around, reading reviews and specs, I decided to go with the A10X.

Anything written here has to take one thing into account, and that is: you get what you pay for. I spent about $68 for the tablet.

Pros:
*The price.
*The wifi is excellent. I use it a lot for Netflix and Vudu and I'm very happy with the performance.
*Along with that, the quad core A33 processor seems fast. I have no complaints about what I've seen it do.
*Bluetooth works perfectly. Connected to my headphones with ease.
*Though plastic, it seems to be solidly made, and is rather lightweight.
*A good size, 5000mAh battery. I don't plug in the charger regularly, and it's lasted me for a lengthy period.

Cons:
*The screen. At 1020x600 pixels, the colors and resolution are miserable. Viewing angle are, to put it nicely..... horrible. Straight on, the tablet picture isn't bad, though again, colors are fairly washed out.
*Compatibility. I've tested some games and they work fine. On the other hand, I play The Simpsons: Tapped Out on my other tablet, and it does nothing but force close on the A10X. Very annoying.
*Charging is through a cable provided, not the USB, as with most tablets. If something happens to the charger, you can probably find another, but not as convenient.

Is this tablet a bad buy? Not if you're looking for something that is very low price, and does the basics. For someone looking for a first time tablet, you could find worse. For a seasoned tablet owner, you will probable find it lacking.

One last note. Please don't trust reviewers that say they got a review copy and are doing an honest review. They're not.

product_title: niceEshop(TM) 6 Buttons 2000 DPI Wired Gaming Mouse LED Optical Game Mice (Black,Blue Dotted)
review_body:
I ordered the black with white dots version of this mouse for $5.61. Looks like space somewhat. Shipping was stated to be 1-4 months, but I received this in two weeks. I'm guessing the long estimate is because they don't declare the package delivered until much later than it's arrival. Only had this mouse for a few days and the entire family likes it. Finger ridges for thumb, ring and pinky finger work great. Braided cord is fairly easy to let go of the sharp bends from packaging. Couple of points need to be made clear, though.

1.) I can't tell what the DPI settings for this mouse are other than that the highest setting is 2000, but I have four different settings rather than the three stated. Little plus.

2.) There is a ridge in the decorated portion of the mouse, running from just under the DPI button all the way down to the bottom. The point at the bottom of the mouse in the picture can help clarify. The ridge juts upward slightly, so it's nearly impossible to hold this with a flat palm comfortably. Shift your palm to the left a little when setting your hand down and it will be fine.

3.) The colors on mine cycle. Yeah, BIG plus on aesthetics. Starts off at red, then green, and yada yada. There must be two different LED's or something inside, because there's a different cycle rate for different areas of the mouse. The scroll wheel and thumb buttons eventually become uncoordinated with the "Weyes" emblem and the lines on either side. Three different rectangles at the bottom back of the mouse usually show the color of the logo, but when it's red there is a bit of bleeding from the scroll wheel color on the right of the middle rectangle. I personally don't care about the change in cycle rate, I think it's a cool defect if anything

4.) The scroll wheel feels cheap and actual scrolling quality leaves something to be desired. When scrolling very fast, the sensor tends to read your scroll in the opposite direction i.e. if you're scrolling down the page will start to go up. Certain games such as Waframe seem to really pronounce this problem. For games, I would program any "next" or "previous" options to the front and back keys. Scroll wheel click is fine

Overall, you can't go wrong with this mouse. The edge and scroll wheel are barely even cons. Shipping time is a bit long if you get used to a five day max but not a deal breaker at all. Give this a go; you won't regret it.f you're scrolling down the page will start to go up. Certain games such as Waframe seem to really pronounce this problem. For games, I would program any "next" or "previous" options to the front and back keys. Scroll wheel click is fine

Overall, you can't go wrong with this mouse. The edge and scroll wheel are barely even cons. Shipping time is a bit long if you get used to a five day max but not a deal breaker at all. Give this a go; you won't regret it.

product_title: TP-Link OnHub AC1900 Wireless Wi-Fi Router
review_body:
To establish some background, I love gadgets and I love reviewing them. I also happen to have a pretty favorable view of the Google gadgets I've used so far: the Nexus phones and tablets, Chromebooks and the Chromecast. And Google's Chrome is the default browser on my Windows laptop. If this could indicate some bias well... I am always trying to be fair and objective when evaluating a new product and I jumped at the opportunity to try out Google's OnHub because it's the first Google router so it's something new. What follows are my impressions.

By the way, I've used, tested and evaluated a number of routers in the past, mostly Netgear, TP-Link and Linksys and a few off-brand models.

FIRST IMPRESSIONS

The first thing that you will notice when taking the OnHub out of the box is how pretty it is. Many routers that I've used including my current Netgear Nighthawk look good but near all of them have the industrial good looks and are meant to be kept out of sight, preferably in the basement. OnHub is living room pretty because Google wants you to keep it some place near the center of your house so that everybody could get a good signal. I would love to be able to take my router out of the basement but it wouldn't be so easy for me because that's where out Internet tap happens to be but, anyone whose Internet connection is in the living quarters would have a good reason to be happy with the OnHub because it should feel like it belonged on a bookshelf or some other visible place. My unit has a dark blue skin but it's removable and easily replaceable and I suspect that alternative shells will be available in the future.

Now, for the setup, this 802.11ac device is designed to do most of the dirty setup work by itself, out of sight and out of mind because most of us have better things to do. It's done through an Android or iOS app and it's as simple and friendly as any router setup has ever been, couple of minutes to set it up. Once operational, the app tells me who/what is connected to my networks, how much bandwidth is taken by each device, even how good a bandwidth I have. For example, it advised me to ask my provider for a higher bandwidth service because what I have now was not good enough to support Ultra HD.

Operation can be super-easy if you only want to do the basic things. Should be able to allow others to remotely manage the router through the phone app but I didn't try it yet. On the finer points, there is no QoS (quality of service) per se but you can reserve bandwidth to certain devices if needed. No parental control features yet. And, something that I wish it was there, I wasn't able to assign different network names for the 2.4GHz and the 5GHz bands which is what I currently have on my other router setup. One network name to rule them all is good from an ease of use point of view but it would be better if the one network setting was the default but we still had the ability to segregate the bands if we chose to do so. Operation/control is overall 'good' for most users and I suspect it's only going to get better as the software gets updates and more features are supported.

As for performance, it's almost as good as our current router but that is a more expensive beast and a more mature product so, no surprises there. I can't place the OnHub anywhere other than the basement but I could easily connect a signal booster to it and everything was good and smooth. For anyone who cares about tech details, this router has 13 (thirteen!) antennas, half a dozen each for the 2.4GHz and 5GHz bands with the 13th beaming a strong signal and, allegedly, constantly attempting to detect an overcrowded channel in use and switch you off of it. It's expected to support Bluetooth in the future but not now. Also noted that it comes with 4GB of internal storage. The USB port can't be used to attach anything to it at this time.

For ports... well... this is supposed to bea near-pure Wi-Fi router so there aren't too many. Besides the unusable USB port and Ethernet in and Ethernet out and that's just about it. Didn't try to attach anything to USB but I did successfully expand/split the Ethernet port by attaching a small switch to it.

MY RATING AND EVALUATION

The OnHub gets an excellent (5 stars) rating for its looks and ease of setup and operation. Without exaggerating much, anyone who can use a phone should have no problem whatsoever setting up and operating this router. The Android app is friendly and, while not providing too many details on the router's operation upfront, it manages to keep me informed about things that I really care such as bandwidth utilization and who's connected to the router at any given time.

Signal strength is good. I won't say that better than our Nighthawk's but, had we had the ability to place the OnHub in a more central area in the house, we would have had a stronger signal. The 13 antennas are internal, by the way, so there's no need to optimally position them by hand and that does add to the 'ease of use' aspect.

My main beef at this time is the lack of physical ports. Wi-Fi routers, traditionally, come with 4 Ethernet ports and a couple of USBs. Yes, most of the devices in our house are wireless but, believe it or not, some do need or at least benefit greatly from a wired attachment. In our case there's a VoIP box, a NAS (network attached storage) and a Powerline adapter wired-connected and that's 3 ports. The 4th is taken by a mini-router we had to use because our iFit-ready treadmill would not talk to the main router but was able to connect to the mini-router. Yes, you can plug in a Hub but that kind of defeats the goal of 'few wires' and slightly complicates everything.

My current rating is 4 stars, with one star deducted for the lack of (needed) physical ports, for the lack of an interface that would give an almost-geek like me more control over the settings and for what I would say is too high a price.a near-pure Wi-Fi router so there aren't too many. Besides the unusable USB port and Ethernet in and Ethernet out and that's just about it. product_title: Corsair Vengeance M65 Performance FPS Gaming Mouse
review_headline: So far this mouse has been great for me
review_body:
So far this mouse has been great for me. Upgraded from a Cyborg Rat7 that I had for years, and this mouse has done exactly what the Rat7, plus a few other things.

Pros:
Easy to use: The Corsair interface is really simple. It will give you 3 menus, DPI, LIGHTING, PROFILE. You use DPI to adjust the sensitivity, and can have 5 different sensitivities bound to each profile, that you switch between with the colored dot right behind the mouse wheel. Lightning you use to color code your mouse however you like, even has a rainbow option. Profile is were you select which profile to use, which the profile is just your saved DPI setting and color coding, and I find that I like to keep a very high DPI for my desktop, and 3 varying speeds for different games, so 1 profile was enough for me, but you can have as many as you like.

Sniper Button: I really enjoy the sniper button on the left side of the mouse, I use it all the time when I play CSGO to help me watch a hallway with a scoped gun, I tend to twitch before I shoot a bit when my nerves get high so its nice to have to lower the twitch.

2 Extra mouse buttons: While 2 isnt a whole lot for when I play RPGs and make good use of the keymapping, the 2 it gives are a big plus for simple things games with multiple alt_fire buttons.

Cons: I haven't run into any yet, and am just passing the 6th month mark.

Overall its a very good mouse for shooters, especially at the price

product_title: Sinoguo Gray Felt & Real Leather Carrying Bag Case Sleeve Pouch Protector Holder for Macbook Pro / Macbook Air / Macbook Pro with Retina Display and Most Popular 13-13.3 Inches Laptop / Notebook / Ultrabook /Netbook, Plus the Adapter Package for Power Adapter / Moblie Phone / Charger or Mouse
review_headline: Not Good Protection, But Cute & Good For Light Use
review_body:
I got the 13- 13.3" size. My laptop is actually only 11.6" So I had a lot of wiggle room in mine. At first I thought it might have been too big, but reading the many comments on here talking about how they ordered the 15-15.6" one but it didn't fit their 15.6" laptop, I was kind of glad that I got the bigger sized one. Here are some of the things I like and dislike about this:

Liked:
-Design: I thought the design was cute, but not "girly". I like that its gender neutral.
-Extra Bag: I like that it came with a matching adapter bag, but unfortunately it was too small to fit my charger for the laptop, it however fit my mouse just fine.
-Quality: I'd say overall quality of the material, stitching, etc. is good. You do have to consider this is FELT. So for felt, this is pretty thick. Its thicker than your typical craft felt. You cannot compare it to things such as leather or vinyl.

Dislikes:
-All Felt Fabric: Please note that this is ALL felt! When it says "felt & real leather' the "real leather" part is just that orange strap going down the middle you see in the picture. It serves no purpose. The case itself is felt inside and out. There is no additional lining on the inside, it is that exact same grey felt you see in the picture in and out.
-Single Magnetic Closure: Obviously with this design you can see which end is up pretty easily but in case you pick this up upside-down by accident, the closure is not as secure as a zipper one. I don't think the one magnetic clasp is strong enough to prevent the laptop from falling out.
-Narrow: My laptop is about .50" thick, and once I close the clasp it didn't poke up or anything but this is a very narrow "pouch", and I can see thicker laptops not fitting. There is a second pocket on the inside right above the main pocket but because this pouch is so thin I can't see you being able to put anything in that pocket unless its paper.

I don't travel too much with my laptop so this case works for me. Its just something to put my laptop in so it doesn't collect dust on my desk. If you are looking for something that really does a good job "protecting" then I don't think this is it. But for light use, I think its fine.

(*I purchased this item with my own money at a discount in exchange for my honest review and opinion)

product_title: CM Storm  - LED Gaming Keyboard and Mouse Combo
review_body: A wonderful keyboard and mouse combo for the price. The keyboard and mouse are very comfortable and responsive, and feel very well made. The keyboard has a very sturdy feel, without making the keys too hard too press. The mouse has rubber grips on each side if the mouse, making long sessions of mouse usage feel very comfortable even after several hours of use. As always, the bundle does have its flaws, such as the keys being very hard to distinguish when the backlight is on, the mouse LED cannot be toggled, and in order for the keyboard's LEDs to turn on, scroll lock must always be activated, which could cause some problems with certain programs. Overall, it's a great bundle that feels and looks great. Definitely a great buy for anybody who wants a good mouse and keyboard without breaking the bank.

product_title: K740 Illuminated Wired Keyboard, USB, Black
review_body:
Very nice keyboard. Typing on this is easy, however there are a few keys that have more surface area than actual button underneath and they make a semi-loud clack noise. The spacebar and backspace seem to have the domes under them placed in a weird spot. I have not attempted to remove any keys yet. The keys do not feel odd, their faces are uniform and I rarely notice the etching for the letter on the top.

The backlight is very bright, visible under normal room lights. There is an option to dim them as well, for 3 levels of brightness and an off position, however you need to cycle through these, there is no on/off.

The plastic on the wrist area is slightly textured, giving it a bit of a rubber feel, but it is not sticky. I kinda wish the clear plastic border for the board wasn't there, but that's a personal aesthetic desire.

The feet don't raise up the keyboard too much, maybe a half inch. The feet themsleves are small, but the have the same rubber on the tips as the boards other feet do, and it is very slide resistant.

I have been using this for gaming and notice no ghosting issues. I do not believe this keyboard has anti ghosting, but it has not been an issue. I play shooters, rpgs and many other types of games with no issue.

It works well with the Logitech keyboard software, I like the feedback HUD whenever I push caps lock on accident, it is a nice large transparent square at the bottom of my screen. I believe this might be able to be customized, however I left it as default.

I'm hoping to keep this keyboard for years and years, just like their other hardware purchases that I have made.

product_title: Genius GX-Gaming SW-G2.1 3000 with Two Input Jacks for PC/TV/DVD/Game Devices
review_body: For what you are paying for them, these speakers are incredible.  I tested the issue that some people are reporting with other sets going into sleep mode. The speakers will go into a sleep mode if the input volume is too low. This can be rectified by making sure your input volume is around 50% or higher. I usually keep the input volume around 75% and adjust volume with the included control unit, and have not experienced this issue (other than recreating it for testing). As others noted, the system has a good mid range, moderate bass, but is some what lacking in the high range. It could probably even use a little more amp than what it came with, with out much distortion.

product_title: ARRIS SURFboard DOCSIS 3.0 Cable Modem (SB6121) Time Warner Cable,.
review_headline: Works well with comcast, two things you need to remember.  MAC & Power reset!
review_body: Worked like a charm if you just take your time and give a call to Comcast.  By default you need to configure this by plugging in your laptop directly to the modem.  Because your laptop was the first device that plugged into the modem it will save your laptop as the default device.  What this means is that once configured you can't just plug in your wireless router and get wifi going.  YOU MUST, configure it with your laptop, call comcast and give them the ARRIS Surfboard MAC address AND THEN unplug the ARRIS Surfboard from power for a good ten minutes.  This will allow it to clear the laptop as the saved device and then take your wifi router.  Enjoy.

product_title: Apple Keyboard with Numeric Keypad MB110LL/B
review_body: Before buying my first Mac, I'd always used basic PC's and whatever peripherals came packaged with them. My Mac mini came with no peripherals. It didn't seem fully compatible with my junky old HP keyboard. This keyboard is a revelation. I love the feel of the keys, their firm touch and rssponsive-ness make typing much easier. What bothers me is the white color. It's dirty already, and I'm a very regular hand-washer. Yes, I could buy a heavy ugly plastic cover to type through; but that's like the ladies who keep their good living room furniture set encased in plastic so it won't get soiled. Completely undoes the beauty of the design. In general, I'm quite bemused by Apple design. I believe that function is as vital as beauty, and that the two must go hand in hand. Early iPhones with exquisite forms and plastic backs that scratch so easily that they must be hidden in those ghastly jelly cases? The sleekly elegant Mac mini that comes with no peripherals built in and only a few USB slots, so you need to add a big USB hub and an ugly tangle of cables for the back-up drive, keyboard, mouse, speakers, CD player, card reader, photo and laser printers. Enough of my Apple rant. The keyboard is smudged and glorious.

product_title: Kindle Paperwhite
review_body:
I really like the back-lit screen; the illumination is even and there's no glare; it can be adjusted to fit the ambient level of light.

As a book reader it's good. I still have my old Kindle with the buttons to compare with. I like the buttons a bit more than the tap of the Paperwhite but I like the Paperwhite screen and text more than the old Kindle's.

The web browser uses a different interface than the book reader which has confused me. For example, when you want to get more of the page, you 'swipe up' instead of 'tap for next page'. In the Kindle store a swipe-up motion often is taken as a tap-to-select motion and I often find that I can't use links on pages (e.g. on the page of results from a Google search). I tap the link but it's not selected and not gone-to. You will probably say "Of course, it's not a tablet", and I will agree but the old Kindle can go through a link on a page, once you 'mouse' down to it with the five-way selector.

I got this because I wanted the lit screen and the smaller form-factor. I'm quite happy with it for those reasons.

review_headline: Easy set-up. Fast and so far reliable
review_body: Pros: Easy set-up. Fast and so far reliable. Cons: Manual is a bit wordy and also did not include a FAQ for common issues/setup problems.  I had to replace my D-Link Dual Band N router because it was old and there were so many networks in the area interfering dropping my connection. Straight out of the box, the router was easy to set up and everything was clearly labeled. I got the router up and running connected within about 10 minutes. The only problem I did have was figuring out where to change the passwords since I didn't want to leave any default password settings and have people jump on my network. It took me a few minutes to get used to the interface of the network manager but finally found it. I apparently mistyped the admin password when I was changing it (there was only 1 field and no confirmation of entering the password again to ensure they are the same) and I ended up going on the internet trying to find how to reset to the default password and get it up and running again.  Aside from that with this router, I haven't experienced any lag times or connection drops yet. Granted it's only been a few days but so far I'm happy with this. Will update if any issue arises.

product_title: iGadgitz Aluminium Adjustable Portable Tablet & Smartphone Folding Holder Stand
review_headline: Good for phones, especially handy for tablets
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:7c6c6734821df151f9829d1118952d12]]The adjustable stand is well made of heavy gauge aluminum and sturdy plastic. The back rotates and locks into position for viewing at different angles. The detents that lock the back are set approximately 15 degrees apart, so there's a good choice of viewing angles. The stand is small (3.9\\"x3.5\\"x1.4\\") and lightweight (6.05 ounces), so it's easily portable enough for carrying in a bag or purse.

I used the stand with my smartphone and my Kindle Fire HDX 7\\" tablet. My smartphone is in a thin rubberized case that fit in the curved slot at the base of the stand. The tablet is in a slimline cover that fit in the slot, but I think that many tablets would have to be removed from a cover to fit. If the rubber-lined slot at the base of the stand isn't wide enough, the rubber insert is easily removed to increase the size of the slot. Both the phone and the tablet worked well in the portrait and landscape orientations. The stand is heavy enough and sturdy enough to work with larger tablets without tipping over - I tried it with a 10\\" tablet, and it was fine. Note that the product description indicates that the foldout can be adjusted to an angle precision of 1 degree. However, it appeared to me that the detents that lock the back into position are set about every 15 degrees.

This is a very handy stand for smartphones and tablets. It's sturdy, and it's small enough and light enough to carry easily in a purse or backpack. The stand is ideal for supporting a phone or tablet in a position for viewing videos or Skyping. It's also an excellent way to hold a phone or tablet while using a wireless keyboard.

The adjustable stand was provided to me for evaluation. I did not promise to post a review, but I stated that if I did review the product, it would be an honest, unbiased review.

product_title: Kindle Case - OMOTON All-new Kindle (7th Gen) Smart Case Cover - The Thinnest and Lightest PU Leather Case Cover for All-new Kindle (New Touchscreen Display, 2014 Released), with Auto Sleep/ Wake Feature, Rose Red Map Case
review_body:
Review updated 1/20/2016:

I have two Omoton cases now. I originally bought the "red rose map" case in August of 2015. When one of the corners cracked last week, I decided to purchase another one, so I got the "magic forest/spring tree" case.

Note: I contacted Omoton and the are replacing the red rose map case at no cost... Great customer service! It's good to have a backup so I'm glad a ordered a new one too!

To compare the two cases:

The red rose map one has a harder, more rigid case. The inside is a soft, fuzzy material that keeps the kindle from getting scratched. The design is pretty and the kindle fits perfectly, flush with the case. It has a magnet closure that sticks out a little on the right so you can easily open the case. No sharp edges. The corner mysteriously cracked though, but again the company offered to replace at no cost since the case wasn't dropped or anything. The case is light and the outside is sightly textured.

The "magic forest/spring tree" case isn't as rigid... More rubbery than just hard plastic, apparently because this is an "updated" case and the rubber is supposed to prevent the case from scratching the kindle, though I didn't have that issue with the harder case. The inside is a soft material, the kindle fits perfectly, flush with the case, and it closes with a magnet. The case doesn't jut out at all, but it's easy enough to open. The case feels a little heavier than the red rose map case, and the material feels softer without sacrificing protection.

The wake/sleep function works perfectly, opening and closing the case, and both cases are pretty, fit my 7th gen kindle perfectly, and are very pretty!

I've very happy with this company and the cases, and I'm glad they stand by their products!

product_title: Macbook Air or Macbook Pro (13 inch) Vinyl, Removable Skin - Lace
review_headline: Good quality product and well packaged.
review_body: Product arrived on time and well packed.  Looks like it's a very good quality skin (having a 3m sticker paper as shown on the back).Will try to install it and make an update.  Update: Sept. 4.  Installed it on my wife's MBP.  It's beautiful with the material (3m) being tough and sticks very well. I installed it without any bubbles using only my hands.  The way I did it was start from one of the edge ( the one near to me) and peeled the backing about 2 inches, aligned from the edge of the MBP, have somebody just lightly press the tntire length on the edge.  Then when seemingly it looks alighned, I started running my fingers pressing the skin, much like how a printer printed on paper, slowly edge to edge.  Then, peeled off another 2 inches, then run my finger again edge to edge.  I kept doing the is until the end. So I didn't need to used the tool that came with it and there were no bubbles.  I then God a dry cloth and wiped it putting moderate pressure on the edges and corners.  Everything came out quite nice!  My wife loved it!

product_title: Neewer Black 19 Pin USB 3.0 Female To 9 Pin USB2.0 Male Motherboard Cable Adapter Converter
review_headline: You might not need it, but if you do, it works.
review_body:
So this is effectively an extension cable for USB 3.0 headers that only includes the 2.0 pins. It does exactly what it says!

However, just so everyone knows, you can plug in USB 3.0 headers into USB 2.0 headers with the right orientation, provided there is room on one side for the extra unused USB 3.0 pins. My motherboard didn't have any room on either side, though, so I needed this. Check before you spend the 5 bucks.

review_body: I purchased these usb cables as replacement cables for our 3 Kindle Fires and my new S6 Edge.  I love the fact that the cables come in different colors as it is easy for my kids and myself to recognize which charger is ours.  The feel of the cable is very nice and they are very flexible.  However, for our Kindle Fires and for my phone I have fast chargers.  When I replace this cable (while still using the fast charging power adapters) with either Kindle's fast charger cable or my phone's fast charger cable I get a notification stating that my device is connected to a low power charger.  Interestingly enough if I replace the cables back to the originals that came with the devices my chargers function fast as expected.  I'm not sure how or why these cables are causing that issue but it is a pain unless we are charging them overnight while we are sleeping since they aren't in use.  Another issue we encountered was these cables not holding a snug fit into the devices we used them on and they were easy to fall out of the port.  Overall these cables aren't bad but they certainly aren't the best.  These would work great for PC use but I can't say I would really recommend them for charging use given our experiences with multiple devices.

product_title: Saitek Pro Flight Yoke with Three-Lever Throttle (PZ44)
review_headline: Good product but large "null zone" in "X" and "Y" axis.
review_body:
I bought this yoke to use it in my Flight Simulator Software in my Mac (X-plane). The quality is quite good although it came with a very wide "null zone" which means there is a very large neutral area where the X and Y axis do not move at all (pitch and roll in an airplane). This is not normal in any other joystick/Yoke since most of them replicate a real airplane yoke which in real life have a little or almost no "null zone". After adjusting any possible option in X-plane software I called tech support who offered me good help but no other solution that to send it back in order to be repaired under warranty.
Reading other past reviews I realized that this issue is an old one (over 3 years old issue) and I can´t understand why Saitek has not addressed it yet!
If we leave aside the "large null zone" issue in X and Y axis, the unit has an excellent quality and good functionality. The three lever control is smooth and works awesome.
Saitek/Mad Catz: I think it is time for you to review your program code in the internal electronics! This is not a potentiometer or mechanical issue but a firmware issue. Please check other threads about this issue which has been solved by other users using bypassing the original USB controller and using an alternate controller with excellent results (Leo Bodnar´s BU836A 12 Bit Joystick Controller.

product_title: Black/Black Survivor for Kindle Fire HDX 7" (2013 Model)
review_headline: Screen cover too small; NOT waterproof; speakers buzz and barely audible. Clearly designed by morons.
review_body:
The product arrived on time and appeared to be the same one pictured.
1.)The biggest issue is that the clear portion of the screen protector was designed very poorly by morons who were unaware or did not care what the actual touch screen size is. You cannot access the drop down menu by swiping the top of the screen, you can't access notifications, clock, etc. AT ALL, you cannot access the quick side menu that allows you to return home or to another open app, and if your apps have any need to you to swipe from the edge of the screen, forget about it. This case is nice if you're going to watch a video and not touch the screen. If you want a protector that allows you to have a protected, functional and usable fire tablet, this is NOT the one for you. It was clearly designed by idiots who did not even check their product specifications to see how much of the touch screen has to be visible in order to use your tablet at all.
2.) Don't fool yourself though, this isn't 100% waterproof. I dropped the tablet into a sink with water into it while reading a recipe, did NOT fully submerge the tablet, and while the tablet functions, the inside of the case was dripping wet. If I hadn't opened the case quickly and aired out the tablet, who knows what kind of water damage, mold, mildew might have ensued.
3.) The casing around the speakers muffles the sound so it is barely audible at full volume, and actually buzzes a lot louder than the sound you are trying to hear. Again, some genius product engineers at work here, can't even make a speaker cover that doesn't buzz louder than your music.
Overall, I would NOT buy this product again. I recommend you look elsewhere. If what you're looking for is a protective case that will protect your device from water and drops AND leave your device functional enough for even casual use, this is NOT the product for you.
The only way the company could possibly adjudicate this issue would be to redesign the case with more competent engineers and provide a free new design model to everyone who threw away their money on a case that renders their touchscreen edge useless, fails to protect from A HALF INCH of water, and renders their speakers unusable. Anything short of providing a free redesigned product would be highway robbery. Don't buy this. Do yourself a favor.

product_title: JETech 2.4Ghz Wireless Mobile Optical Mouse with 3 CPI Levels and USB Wireless Receiver (0770)
review_body:
I was looking for a replacement for the spare mouse I carry in my bag. I didn't want to spend a whole lot because this is my "spare" and not my daily use one. The thing I liked about this one was the fact that you could place the receiver in the back of the mouse. On the previous model I was using I had to remove the battery cover to access the holder slot for the receiver.

So I ordered this unit. When I got it, it just felt cheap and not as well made as the previous mouse. It takes two AAA batteries instead of the standard single AA all my other mice had. The on/off button is recessed so you have to use a pocket knife to turn it on and off. For someone that uses this mouse for their bag turning it on and off is a requirement and always having to pull out the pocket knife or find a sharp object to turn it off is not always practical. After setup the right and left mouse buttons would not work. It was just not what I expected. So I dinged it 2 stars for those things. Next time I will probably just spend a few dollars more and get the Amazon basics wireless mouse I was using before.

product_title: TP-Link OnHub AC1900 Wireless Wi-Fi Router
review_headline: Very solid router that is worth the $200 asking price.
review_body:
Full disclosure; I am a Google employee and was given one of these to test pre-release.

Having said that, if I were currently in the position to buy a router, I would buy this without hesitation. It has a significantly further range than my previous router (at a similar price point). It's also much easier to configure and set up. I love that I can do a speed test on my network even when not connected to it, and if my ISP goes down, I get a notification of the service interruption on my phone, even if I'm not at home. It's got a 2.4GHz and 5Ghz, and will seamlessly choose the best one under any given circumstances; you don't even need to think about it. Possibly most importantly, it auto-updates (in a similar manner to the Chrome browser), so it gets security patches as soon as they are available.

product_title: Samsung 850 EVO Parent
review_headline: The drive is fine, the data migration tool is junk.
review_body:
I ordered this product for upgrading my daughter's laptop before she returns to her college. This is not my first Samsung SSD - I have a perfectly functional Samsung 840 Pro 500GB installed on my own laptop.

The drive hardware is quite fine. The adjunct software is absolute junk. Let me recount the experience step by step (and some solutions too).
1. First attached the drive using an external Sabrent enclosure to the laptop. The Windows 10 and the Samsung Data Migration refused to recognize the drive. For a drive that is $175 or so, I am surprised that this converter cable did not come with the pack.
2. Then attached the drive to a desktop (Windows 8.1 Pro) as an internal drive. Windows recognized and initialized the drive properly.
3. Then fixed back the drive using the same external enclosure to the laptop, now Windows 10 recognized the drive, but Samsung Data Migration Tool did not find the SSD.
4. A few long wait time calls and I was informed by Samsung that Samsung Data migration does NOT work on Windows 10 - and the very helpful team could not name any product that would migrate the data - and finally suggested that I roll back to Windows 8.1 !
5. I installed a Macrium Reflect Free software and it indicated that Windows 10 installation has 5 partitions (last two made for some additional recovery). But the software will not migrate from a 1TB hard disk (only 261 GB used) to a 500 GB hard disk because, well, because of no reason.
6. Shrank the data partition in the hard disk to 505 GB (would not go any below), then deleted the page file - since it is usually immovable, and then tried to copy only the first three partitions. This worked with a note from the Macrium software that my data partition is being shrunk slightly.
7. Once this step got over, I further shrank the data partition in the SSD by an additional 1 GB to make space for the last two partitions.
8 Finally, again used the Macrium SW to copy the lasttwo recovery partitions made by Windows 10.
9 Replaced the HDD with the SSD, and then restored the page file size to System default. Removed the Macrium Free SW as it was being detected as "adware" by Malwarebytes.

The SSD drive since then is working perfectly. I am absolutely certain that this migration would qualify as an harrowing experience to most people. If Samsung cannot offer a Windows 10 Data migration tool, then perhaps it should withdraw the drive from the market till it has a tool to offer, or make a serious note about it on their website. Honestly, they should also consider shutting down their helpline - its about as helpful as the FCC warning label on the box enclosure of the disk - costs money, achieves nothing.
I have not had the courage to run the other SW that came along with - Samsung Magician - as am quite wary of these.

product_title: Logitech G502 Proteus Core Tunable Gaming Mouse with Fully Customizable Surface, Weight and Balance Tuning
review_body:
This might be the most perfect mouse I have ever held in my hand. The shape may look edgy and uncomfortable, but the way it is designed, it almost conforms to my hand. However, if you like to claw-grip, this mouse is not for you.

I like my mice on the heavy side, and Logitech provides just enough weights to make that happen. Specifically, there are five 3.6 g weights that can be moved around the mouse or removed entirely. It allows for a lot of customization. Also, the dpi settings are ridiculous. I don't think I have ever used a mouse that can be this accurate, especially not an optical mouse. The side buttons on gaming mice usually get in the way, but these are positioned in such a way as to be out of the way when you don't want them but within a thumb rolls reach when you do.

Overall, I would recommend this mouse to anyone. It does its job better than any other mouse I have seen.

product_title: AmazonBasics USB Hub
review_body:
As an electrical engineer, some times I have to power a lot of things from my computer.

Development Boards for microprocessors usually use 2 ports(1 for power and 1 for data), my oscilloscope uses 1 port, my wireless devices use a few more and my phone charger uses another. My laptop only has 3 usb ports so this is a problem. I bought this device specifically because it has the ability to use an external power supply (wall outlet). This is optional in use, but if you are using your hub to power objects I would recommend its use. Since a usb plug min a laptop is limited to about a 1/4 amp, they cannot power a lot of devices at the same time. This fixes the problem easily and allows you to use your computer in new ways.

It can also be used to charge multiple devices from a wall outlet i.e. does not have to be plugged into your computer for operation.

The drivers install easy and overall I have not had any problems with this product.

product_title: Logitech Wireless Solar Keyboard K750
review_body:
I will just start by saying this is an awesome keyboard. I very highly recommend it. It is not perfect, but if I were to give it a rating out of ten it would be somewhere in the line of a 8/10. I've used this keyboard for about half a year and I love it. Below I will list the pros and cons of it and what kind of a person should buy this keyboard.
Pros:
-FREAKING SOLAR! Works well even in low light rooms.
-NO batters because of solar. It's hard to explain how nice this is until you own the thing.
-Has a build in solar level indicator
-Has the ability to manually turn the keyboard on and off from a switch built into the keyboard
-Has fairly good range. I personally have not had any trouble using it, even though two different desks
-Nice shortcut keys for PC Power, Volume control, Calculator shortcut, as well as E-Mail and Search shortcuts
-No cords on your desk surface :)
Cons:
-Not a super sturdy construction, only meant as a relatively fixed keyboard on your desk
-Plastic surface gets easily scratched and like many other keyboards, it's not the easiest thing to clean. <--These are my biggest issues
-Chiclet Keys which may not be your thing, they work great for me and typing feels comfortable so its hard to put this as a con

So who should buy this keyboard? This keyboard works well for an office computer as well as an in home computer for general use. It can be used for gaming (I do some light gaming on it. Occasional Skyrim, Minecraft, Age of Empires, Ect) although it obviously is not a gaming keyboard. It also is not for those who like more traditional keys on their keyboard. As I mentioned earlier it does have the more chicklet styled keys. If you are using this for general use computing I can't recommend it enough. The money you can save from battery powered keyboards and the niceness of not having another cord run across your desk is WELL worth the purchase of this keyboard.

product_title: 13.3" HP 13-r010dx x2 Detachable Laptop Tablet Intel Core i3-4021Y 4GB RAM 500GB + 8GB Hybrid HDD BeatsAudio Bluetooth Windows 8.1 Snow White/Ash Silver (Certified Refurbished)
review_body: I've been a lifelong fan of HP, but this is probably the worst computer I've ever gotten from them.  At least once a week, it encounters a problem and shuts down while I have important things open that I'm working on (this has been happening since I got it from the box).  This is probably the biggest issue.  Besides that, several drivers have had to be reinstalled since I bought it, just a few months ago.  The touchscreen is really too heavy for the keyboard, and as a result it tends to fall backward on any soft surface (like my lap), and is very tippy on hard surfaces too.  The touchscreen is okay...but it tends to be a bit "sticky".  It's not glass like most smartphones are, so my finger tends to drag and leave smudges much more easily, and after a while of using it, the touchscreen gets jumpy and buggy because of this.  It also makes it hard to be precise with the touchscreen.  The power button is quite difficult to use as well - sometimes if it's on sleep, I press it and the computer comes back immediately.  Other times, I press it and nothing happens after a few moments, so I end up pressing it a few times trying to make it come back to life and the computer inevitably ends up restarting itself (again a pain).  Also, and this is such a tiny issue, but has bugged me - about two weeks after I got it, one of the rubber feet fell off the bottom, so now it's a bit lopsided, even though it's still quite new.  All in all, this is just not HP's best offering at all.

product_title: Simbans (TM) S75W 7 Inch Quad Core Tablet PC - 1GB, 8GB, HD, HDMI, Android 4.4 KitKat - Manufacturer Refurbished
review_headline: Great little Tablet and value for money.
review_body:
Excellent service and product. Could not ask for faster postage and solid packaging.
The Tablet is exactly as described and runs like a dream. Lots of power for such a small unit and build quality was very good. The screen is HD as described, but as some other reviews have mentioned you do have to be looking at it almost straight on to get the best view. It is too shiny...like a glossy photo that you have to hold at just right angle to see properly. It is something that I have gotten used to quickly though.
I use the Tablet mainly for reading books on Kindle and the screen is excellent for that. The only other thing is the battery life. It is just as Simbans advertise at about 4 to 6 hours. But what they don't mention is that it does charge very quickly!
Over all I am very happy with my new Simbans Tablet. I did not buy it expecting a $500 Tablet for $49.95, but what I did get exceeded my expectations.

product_title: Security Pure Black and White Ultra Slim Laptop Cooling Pad with 5 Blue LED Fans, Dual USB 2.0 Ports Powered Laptop Computer cooler for 11- 17 Inch Notebook (Black)
review_headline: ~~ Variable speed fans enhance this cooler ~~
review_body:
With four fans blowing air and one larger fan sucking air, this laptop cooler does the job. At approximately 14 3/4" x 10 1/2" our 17" laptops do hang over the edge a little, but not enough to be detrimental. I was pleasantly surprised at the noise level. In other words it was quiet. A nice feature is the ability to change the speed of the fans. Personally I think this is more likely to be set once and left alone, rather than changed when your machine gets hot, but that is great as different machines run hotter than others.

Cons: Unlike some laptop coolers this one is not conducive to using on your lap, the design of the 'feet' make it a little uncomfortable on your legs. Like a lounge chair it has an adjustable back so that you can have your laptop at the angle that is most comfortable for you. This of course creates extra height so your arms are higher when you are typing etc.

Product provided in exchange for an honest review. Thanks, Richard

product_title: ROSEWILL ATX Case , Mid Tower Case with Blue LED Fan / Gaming Case for PC with Side Window Panel & 3 Fans Pre-Installed , Computer Case 2 x USB3.0 Port - NAUTILUS
review_headline: Great case. Fits HUGE Noctua nh-d15!!
review_body:
Great case from Rosewill. I have done a build with the original Challenger case, and was impressed.
This one impressed me more though.
The main thing I love about this is the roomy width it offers, while being a bit shorter. I do not like the hugeness of full towers. This is one of the shortest mid towers that I could find at 16 " high.
The extra room that the side panels offer is awesome, as it not only allows more cable management, but air cooling options are phenomenal.
I first threw a CM Hyper Evo 212 in this, and was impressed at the space I still had.....
So, I measured and took a chance to try the Noctua nh-d15s (probably the biggest air cooler you can buy).
And it fit!
I have been changing out things on this case for 2 months now, and find it very easy to work with for it's size.
I have changed out the fans, as I am a silence freak.
The fans that came with it were actually quieter than a few fans that I replaced them with, until I went with Corsair Quiets.
This does not mean the Rosewill fans were loud. This means I am a silence freak.

PROS: Great looking design.
Will fit under any desk.
The size of this thing is perfect for those who don't want a tank under their desk.
You can add so many fans, it would be overkill.
Fits largest air cooler I could find!
Fits big graphics "cards". I have a evga 970 ftw+ in it on the top slot.
Removable hard drive rack. (I kept it)
The fans included are better than some I purchased.
Quite easy to work with.
Price!

CONS:
Not windowed. I just wish it were.
Motherboard standoffs may need a wrench, as some are not threaded well. I had a wrench though, so no big ;)
I did not try liquid cooling, but it looks like a top 240 may be tough to fit....although I thought this about the air cooler I install.

Damn good case from Rosewill that does not get the due it's deserved.
I have seen many people complain about the standoffs. I have a wrench. Bet you do too.e seen many people complain about the standoffs. I have a wrench. Bet you do too.

product_title: MSI Computer ATX DDR3 1066 LGA 1150 Z97A GAMING 7 Motherboard
review_headline: 3 PCI 3.0 slots, USB 3.1, High quality, dream BIOS..what's not to love here?
review_body: 3 PCI 3.0 slots, USB 3.1, High quality, dream BIOS..what's not to love here?  I paired this with a Samsung 850 Pro SSD (OS / boot drive), WD Black 3TB 7200 rpm hard drive, Intel Core i7-4790 running stock,  Noctua cooler [[ASIN:B00TBHYYFK Noctua Premium Quality Quiet CPU Cooler for Intel 1150 Socket NH-U9S]],32 GB of GSkill ARES DDR3 2400 RAM, 550 Watt Seasonic power supply.   It's screaming fast.  I am spoiled.   I can have many multimedia windows open and nothing stutters or breaks a sweat (CPU hovers at 50 degrees C , 122 degrees F)  My rig is near silent.  The BIOS is very posh... the graphics, navigation, etc.  I have never had so much information, setting choices (and decent EXPLANATIONS regarding setting choices) BUT!  --> You are ** not **  forced to use all that info it you don't want it.  Just set the time, take the defaults.  It's all good.  For Overclockers and those who want to fuss with settings:  You ** could ** spend most of your adult life manually tweaking the plethora of RAM and CPU parameters here.  I can't be bothered with that, but it's certainly there for those who want it.  OTHER COOL THINGS:  The slot spacings are wide enough you are unlikely to have component spacing conflicts.  There are dual LED hexadecimal readouts that give you codes you can look up to see why something might not be working.  Aside from the excellent functionality, did I mention that it looks flat out great?  MSI gives you two USB 2.0, six USB 3.0 and 2 (two) USB 3.1 jacks, so..those who can't afford a USB hub to begin with have a generous supply of USB ports to work with .  The 3.1 jacks were a deciding factor to me - future proofing without taking up a card slot.  It has an M2 socket but I passed on that.  If you use the MD2 socket, it will eat up Sata connectors 7 and 8.  There is a single PS2 connector that supposedly can be used for either Keyboard or mouse.  (Yes PS2 is ancient but some people have beautiful PS2 input hardware they don't want to part with justyet.).  I didn't bother with the onboard video but you are given a lot of connectors for that.  For audio, I'm using an external DAC but, if I wasn't, the Realtek sound chips have gotten so good that it wouldnt be a bad solution.  The built in Ethernet networking (NIC) is the "Killer" (brand) licensed hardware.  I don't game anymore really so I can't speak to if it's any faster than an Intel NIC but it certainly delivers solid, zippy performance.  I declare this board a winner.  I didn't buy it here at Amazon but I can certainly recommend it.  ADDENDUM:  I got some RAM DISK software and created a 2GB RAM BOOT DISK.   You have to wait a bit for the boot to happen but Gads!  the surfing is blazing fast now.     Very please with how things turned out.

product_title: ASUS G501JW 15-Inch Gaming Laptop [2014 model]
review_headline: Gaming power in an ultrathin laptop
review_body:
Lately it seems like Asus is the brand to beat when it comes to getting exceptional computing hardware at reasonable prices. The ROG G501 isn’t cheap by laptop standards, but considering the hardware Asus has packed into this svelte package the $1,590.00 price tag is quite reasonable.

The 4K display is ahead of its time—as most 4K technology is right now. It sounds impressive, but there just isn’t much practical use for it just yet. Asus provides almost all of the ports and connections you could want on the ROG G501 and the notable exception—the Ethernet port—is still delivered via the included USB dongle.

If you just want an ultrabook capable of running Windows and all of your Windows applications you should look at the Asus Zenbook UX305 for about half the money. If you want all of the horsepower of a desktop and then some in a thin, light portable machine that can blow the doors off of many dedicated gaming machines then you should definitely take a look at the Asus Republic of Gaming G501.

Check out the complete review on TechSpective.net: http://techspective.net/2015/08/31/review-asus-republic-of-gamers-g501-laptop/

product_title: ZyXEL 1100 Series
review_body:
I've been meaning to pick up a dedicated WAP for my apartment, as my old setup of two DD-WRT routers forming a wireless bridge wasn't cutting it range-wise. I read a few good reviews outside of Amazon and decided to try the ZyXEL out after seeing the price drop.

I've had plenty of experience with ZyXEL firewalls but never tried any of their wireless products. My experience level is definitely higher than the average user, so I can't speak for how newbie-friendly this would be.

I picked up the TP-LINK TL-PoE150S PoE injector and it works great with this AP.

The Web GUI will be familiar to anyone who's used their products in the past. Basic setup of the IP address, SSID and security was pretty easy. I let the access point pick a channel automatically, since my area is pretty cluttered with APs.

I installed an Intel 7260.HMWG.R card in my laptop so I could actually use the wireless ac speeds. I was able to transfer files from my hard-wired HTPC at about 10 MB/s.

As for the range, I haven't even mounted the AP on my wall yet and I'm already seeing an insane improvement on the other end of my apartment (which is where I was using a router with DD-WRT as a wireless bridge). I didn't have high expectations for this but it's been great. If you have a larger house, you can surely set these up to work together and extend the range.

No complaints at all so far!

product_title: AMNIE AE-CP1501 15.6"-17" Laptop Cooler - Four Quiet 160mm Fans at 1,200RPM, Ultra-portable and Light Weight (4 Fans)
review_headline: Decent but lacking for larger or warmer laptops
review_body:
I believe that this cooling stand will work quite well for some and so I urge you to know what you are purchasing and read both specs and reviews to determine whether you fall into that category. That being said, I see both positives and negatives to this design and I'll give my impressions based on having tested several laptop coolers over the years. To begin with, I almost always use a cooling stand when doing any real work as I am running a high end graphics laptop that runs on the warmer side (with a high end graphics and two HDD's) and is housed in an aluminum case.

Pros:
The stand is relatively sturdy. It is a mixture of some type of metal and plastic. It is heavy enough not to feel cheap and light enough not to be off-putting. The fans are fairly large and for the most part cover each of the corners to the middle of the stand giving it a large area of coverage (for fan effectiveness, please continue reading below).

The stand comes with a standalone braided usb cable (which should help with wear and tear) which gives plenty of reach from the back of the stand where the USB inputs are to any USB input on your laptop. You will also find the fan controls on the back of the stand near the USB inputs. There is cord management on the bottom center of the stand which is convenient as the USB used to power the stand is not connected permanently on one side and could get lost otherwise.

There are two retractable kickstand-like feet on the bottom of the stand that are meant to keep the fans off whatever surface the stand is resting on. This is a great feature as it increases air flow around the fans on the bottom of the stand which is especially important if you're using this, for example, on your bed on top of a comforter which would leave no space between the bottom of the stand and the material. These "feet" are plastic and while they seem sturdy, I wonder how well they would do with a larger and heavier laptop over the long run. There are also two feet on the top of the laptop (the side that the laptop sits on) which are smaller and also made of plastic. There is no documentation with the stand to explain what these two smaller feet are for and I can only assume it's to counter the slant that is created by the feet on the bottom of the stand (basically, it helps the laptop to sit more flat relative to the surface the cooling stand is on). I've not seen this feature on any of the cooling stands I've used before and I think that it is a smart idea as I do not always want a significant slant when typing as it can cause discomfort in one's wrists (see more on this below).

Finally, the 12-month warranty the AMNIE offers is a very nice feature and I appreciate a company standing behind their products. Could it be longer? Any warranty could always be longer, but I believe at this price point $25-$30, a one-year warranty is absolutely appropriate and one could even argue it's more than appropriate when many electronic components come with 90-day warranties.

Cons:
I found the dimensions of this product to be less than 16" x 11" (and the dimensions are actually listed as slightly bigger than that online). I wish that I had taken a picture of this before returning the product, but I was more concerned with getting a product that would work for my needs as soon as possible. This was a significant issue for me as the description states that it supports a 17" laptop, which I have (I actually pulled out a measuring tape and measured the length and width prior to ordering for this very reason). Had the measurements been spot on, it would have fit perfectly, however it does not. The irregular shape of the stand also adds to issue because a slight overhand is compounded in the areas where the shape angles in towards the center of the stand (in the middle of each side).

With regards to the two retractable kickstand-like feet on the bottom of the stand, as I mention above, I wonder how well they would do with a larger and heavier laptop over time. With regards to the two smaller feet on the top of the stand, I quickly found a design fault. Being that they are smooth plastic and most bottoms on laptop are metal or some other smooth surface, there is absolutely no traction/friction and a laptop could easily side off of these feet if, for example, it was accidentally bumped or while you are moving the stand and laptop. It would have been a simple addition to add a rubber-like pad or some other material/coating on the end of those feet which would create friction. This is a real surprising oversight on the designer's part. Unfortunately, I did not take note of whether this issue exists on the bottom set of feet. However, I feel that this would be less of an issue due to the fact that the feet are larger and therefore have a larger surface area and also have the weight of the stand and the laptop bearing down on them which would impact their stability in this area.

This is personal preference of course, and I will explain why, but I feel that the stand-alone USB power cable is less than ideal. I truly disliked the fact that the cable used to power the stand, a USB cable, is not connected permanently to the cooling stand. You might conclude that not being permanently connection makes it easier to pack up and store and not worry about damaging the connection, but if it were permanently attached, there is no need to have such a vulnerable connection. The connection could be made internally and the only thing protruding would be a malleable cable with one usb connection. This is a design choice of course, but it could become problematic because it makes the cable easier to lose. How many times have you lost or forgotten a cable? But "what about the included cable management" you ask? How many times have you packed up for the night and didn't put everything away because youwere in a hurry or [insert any number of excuses here]. Sure, you can replace this cable, but it is one more expense and it would be a definite inconvenience. Also, again there is the increased chance of damaging the male and female USB components at the stand connection point where there is normally only one (if that cable was internally connected as it is on my current, time tested, laptop cooler).

Finally, perhaps most important (aside from the size issue because if it doesn't fit, what's the point?) is the effectiveness of the fans. As I mentioned previously, I have a laptop that runs warm and sometimes downright hot. If you have a laptop that runs warm-hot, I do not believe this will work for you. I found the fan output to be very week when leaving my hand next to them. That being said, it appeared to keep the surface of the stand (which I believe, if I remember correctly, was some sort of metal) a relatively neutral temperature. So, it's not entirely ineffective, but I can say with certainty that it is not equipped to deal with a laptop that runs quite warm. In case there are any naysayers who will try to make the argument that a laptop shouldn't run that warm/hot and that is a bigger issue, that's really neither here nor there. Some laptops run like that and have since the day they were first powered up. As I said, this cooler isn't ineffective, it's just not going to be effective enough for certain laptops. Also, my GPU is located in the upper left corner of my laptop (under the Escape key essentially) and so I need more cooling in that area than anywhere else. In fact, the rest of my laptop is almost always room temperature. So, I was taking a leap of faith with this cooler stand, hoping that the decent fan coverage in the corners would be enough to do the job...Unfortunately, it wasn't. Since the lighting that accompanies the fan operation is completely unnecessary, I would only make sense to cut out the fancy unnecessary blue lighting and use the extra power to amp up the fan output.

Conclusion:
The AMNIE AE-CP1501 appears to be well built for its price. If you have a laptop less than 16" you should be fine with regards to product dimensions and for the average laptop (not build for serious graphics work or gaming) it will likely do a decent job cooling your machine. In that case, I'd say that if you like the way this looks and the price is right, give it a shot. If you have a 17"+ laptop, I believe that you'll find it runs a bit short which makes managing both the laptop and the cooling stand a bit much and as it is an irregular shape (not a rectangle, but with several additional angles added in for show as opposed to increase air flow), it makes that even more cumbersome. I ended up returning the product and ordering the newest version of the cooling stand I had purchased twice over the last 5 years [[ASIN:B00ED3WMTC Cooler Master NotePal U3 PLUS - Gaming Laptop Cooling Pad with 3 Moveable High Performance Fans (Black)]]). The only reason I purchased something else (the AMNIE cooler) was because I was looking for an alternative that did not come with a fixed incline, but I suppose I learned not to mess with what isn't broken as everything else on it perfectly for my needs and also came with an extended warranty.

product_title: Alfa AWUS036NHA Wireless B/G/N USB Adaptor - 802.11n - 150 Mbps - 2.4 GHz - 5 dBi Antenna - Long Range - Atheros Chipset - Windows XP/Vista 64-Bit/128-Bit Windows 7 Compatible
review_headline: improves my ping, doesnt overheat or die on me randomly, dont forget to install the drivers in the CD
review_body:
The network card inside my vaio laptop died, so I got this external card (these wireless adapters have a network card in them, of course) and I also got a hugeeee USB extension cord separately - doing that is a greatttt idea if you have a router downstairs and your laptop is upstairs and you want to put this adapter wherever the heck you want in your room (or outside your room) to get good signal from downstairs. My ping on league of legends went from 120 with 5k laggspikes, all the way down to 85 ping without a single spike. (And later when they changed the server, down to like 30ping) anyways - this card is great if you HAVE to play games using wifi, it'll improve your latency/ping.

Easy driver installation with the CD that comes in the box.

Oh and it also picks up like 20 different random WIFI signals from around my neighborhood, pretty neat, lol

Ok one last note - INSTALL THE DRIVERS THAT COME WITH THE CD. dont just ignore the CD and expect this card to magically work on its own. I plugged it in WITHOUT installing drivers first, and the upload/download speed was hella slow and the signal was tiny. After I installed the drivers, the speed became supermagically fast, and the signal got really strong. I can even livestream (upload video from my house) on this thing all day nonstop.

product_title: Toshiba Satellite C55-C5241 15.6 Inch Laptop (Intel Core i5, 8 GB, 1TB HDD), Black
review_body:
Before buying this laptop, I had read some good reviews and some not so good, so I had mixed feelings.
Now I had it for a few days and I am very happy with it. Let me explain why.
First the price. It's a deal with this config, Intel I-5, DVD player, 8 Gb RAM, 1 Tb HDD.
For this price, of course I did not expect a SSD, but in a few months, if prices drop down, I may swap the HDD for a SSD.
I won't say anything about Windows 10 because, so far I don't see what is better than Windows 7 that I used with my former laptop. On the contrary, it takes some time to do correct settings if one wants to avoid all the spying which is activated by default.
The laptop seems reasonably happy with 8 Gb RAM. Windows 10 starts in less than 30', including a password. I installed several of my favorite programs, including Microsoft Office and everything works fine.
Some people don't like the keyboard (rubber feeling) but for me it's not really a problem. Yes it reminds me of the first Atari computers in the early 80s. However, what I like is the numeric keyboard.
The screen is bright and OK to view movies. Beware, there is a tiny button to eject the DVD tray, so small that it is almost impossible to see it. To make it more convenient, I stuck a small white mark on it, and now it's okay.
Overall, this laptop is fast enough for most uses. And again for the price it is difficult to beat.

product_title: NETGEAR DOCSIS 3.0 Cable Modem  Bundle
review_headline: Don't bother, go with a different brand
review_body:
I'm giving 2 stars because reliability of this router is bad for a high end product.

I've had this for about 1 year and it works as you would expect most of the times... high speed, long range, etc. Sadly it cannot handle multiple devices using some bandwith concurrently for too long. I've noticed this since I started streaming Xbox one to my W10 PC while also watching streams in HD in multiple devices. The router seems to just not be able to handle the work, everything communication dies for about 10 seconds in every device i have attached and then it comes back to life on its own.

I've also had intermittent issues connecting devices to this router, for some reason it just doesn't allow them to connect at all until I power reset it.

Yes, I constantly check for firmware and software updates, they haven't helped.

I would recommend to people that are looking for a high end router to look somewhere else, this guy will fail you when you most need it for its supposed high end capabilities.

product_title: NeuTab174; K1 10.1 Inch Quad Core Tablet PC Google Android 5.1 Lollipop System 1GB RAM 16GB Nand Flash Dual Camera Built-in Bluetooth 4.0 HDMI Output GPS Supported
review_headline: Great 10 Inch Tablet for the Price
review_body:
***Product Received in exchange for honest review***

Another great tablet from NeuTAB!! I have been asked to test several of their tablets and everyone has been a very well built and nice tablet for the price.. Lets start with a simple breakdown

1.) Display - Display is the lacking point on all tablets for this price point.. The display isn't bad by any means BUT it is lower resolution than you might be used to.. BUT with that being said, NeuTab has about the best display for a tablet in this price range.. The display is sharp (For the resolution), the display is very bright and the display has decent (Not the best) but decent viewing angles.. Overall I have always been impressed with NeuTab displays!

2.) Performance - The tablet has 1 GB of ram and a Quad Core CPU which is plenty unless you plan to do a lot of multitasking.. 1 GB is plenty for games, basic multitasking, basic video editing, photo editing and more.. The quadcore CPU is also plenty for those task.. Gaming wise, I tested 10 of the top 10 downloaded games and all WORKED GREAT!!! I also tested basic video editing from my GoPro camera and then tested basic photo editing using google snapseed and both worked fine!! I then tested a few basic 3d games such as GTA and it played great with no issues.. I am very happy with the performance of this tablet!!

3.) Battery Life - This tablet has GREAT BATTERY life.. I can get a FULL day out of the battery on pretty heavy use.. I can get several hours out of the battery with gaming.. and with basic use I received almost 2 days of battery life!! The 6,000mAH battery is a beast in this tablet..

4.) Memory - Tablet has 16 GB built in which is plenty for apps.. I love watching movies on tablets like this though, so I would recommend a MICRO SD card if you plan on loading a lot of pictures or movies

5.) Streaming Media - This tablet is GREAT for streaming.. Netflix, Amazon Prime Instant Video (and regular instant video), Hulu, Prime Music, Spotify, Pandora where all tested on this tablet and all worked GREAT!! The screen is nice and big making this a great tablet for movies.. The built in speakers also worked very well!!

6.) Bluetooth - This tablet offers bluetooth that worked great! I paired it with several devices without any issues.. Bluetooth Speakers, headphones, keyboards all worked very nicely with this tablet..

7.) Touchscreen - Worked very well and I had no issues with multitouch!

8.) Speakers - The built in speakers are excellent!!

9.) Ports - None of the ports, including the Micro SD card are hidden making it very easy to attach things, charge, and even change micro SD card! This is a feature I love about NeuTab Tablets!

10.) Camera - Camera works OK.. Not the best but neither are the cameras on Kindle Fire tablets.. For a tablet camera it is fine.. The tablet also has a front camera that worked great for SKYPE

11.) Customer Service - I have contacted the NeuTab support team a few times and they are all very friendly, and reply very quickly.. They are very easy to understand.

Overall - a 10 inch tablet for under $100?? and a GREAT one at that!! What do you have to lose! This tablet has a decent screen, full of features, and has an amazing battery!! All for under $100! It is a good tablet for gaming, children, beater tablet.. You name it, this is a decent tablet for it!! I would recommend this to anyone.. Its a great tablet for the price..regular instant video), Hulu, Prime Music, Spotify, Pandora where all tested on this tablet and all worked GREAT!! The screen is nice and big making this a great tablet for movies.. The built in speakers also worked very well!!

6.) Bluetooth - This tablet offers bluetooth that worked great! I paired it with several devices without any issues.. Bluetooth Speakers, headphones, keyboards all worked very nicely with this tablet..

7.) Touchscreen - Worked very well and I had no issues with multitouch!

8.) Speakers - The built in speakers are excellent!!

9.) Ports - None of the ports, including the Micro SD card are hidden making it very easy to attach things, charge, and even change micro SD card! This is a feature I love about NeuTab Tablets!

10.) Camera - Camera works OK.. Not the best but neither are the cameras on Kindle Fire tablets.. For a tablet camera it is fine.. The tablet also has a front camera that worked great for SKYPE

11.) Customer Service - I have contacted the NeuTab support team a few times and they are all very friendly, and reply very quickly.. They are very easy to understand.

Overall - a 10 inch tablet for under $100?? and a GREAT one at that!! What do you have to lose! This tablet has a decent screen, full of features, and has an amazing battery!! All for under $100! It is a good tablet for gaming, children, beater tablet.. You name it, this is a decent tablet for it!! I would recommend this to anyone.. Its a great tablet for the price..
