product_title: HP Pavilion X2 10.1-inch Detachable 2 in 1 Laptop 32GB
review_body:
I emailed this to HP:

In April, I purchased a 2-1 laptop from Amazon.com. My previous laptop (an HP model) was beat up and on its last legs and I was excited to purchase the 2-1 at a great price and a new HP product.

I received my computer a few dyas later and the keyboard didn't work at all but I knew I had the onscreen keyboard and that was fine. A few weeks after getting the computer I started having issues with the wireless connections. The wireless signal would drop and say "no networks found" whether I was at home using the wireless or at my place of work. Each location would normally show 6 or more networks, yet my new laptop couldn't read any. After using your horrid website for support, I finally found an 800 number to call. I explained the situation with the wireless and keyboard, I was sent a box, shipped it to HP and a week later the computer came back "fixed".

After a week or two, the same thing happened again..."no networks found" once again. The good news was the keyboard worked. Same routine, called, box, ship, repair, shipped back.

A few days later I started having the same wireless issues. At this point, my feeling was the issue is unfixable and when at home I was able to reconnect by going into the control panel. However, calamity struck again as the computer would not turn on at all. I called HP support and explained that the wireless still wasn't fixed and now the computer would not even turn on. I told the outsourced support tech that the computer was a lemon and they needed to send me a new one as a replacement. He asked me where I purchased it from. I told him Amazon.com. He said they couldn't replace it because I didn't buy it from HP. Wait, WHAT? HP will not replace a defective computer that it built? HP will not stand behind its products because I didn't purchase it directly from them?

Your outsourced tech just wanted to trouble shoot the problem, following hisscript instead of listening to the customer and, you know, actuallty trying to help me...I asked him several times to just send me the box so they can "repair" the computer. Finally he sends me to his "supervisor" who wants to trouble shoot....AGAIN. I told her several times to just send me the box, that I already did the trouble shoot with the other guy and it still wouldn't turn on...I repeated to her that the computer was a lemon and they should replace it but she said they wouldn't do that. The call dropped (My phone was the issue-no one on your outsourced end ended the call). This took place on Saturday, August 22nd. I received a voicemail on Wednesday, August 26 from HP support asking me if I still wanted the support ticket open and that they have tried to call me several times. If I was called, no message was left until Wednesday and I generally do not pick up the phone
when I recieve calls from unfamilair numbers, so the effort to reach me was minimal at best and I should have been called back within minutes of the call disconnecting, not hours or days.

Since HP wouldn't stand behind their product I contacted Amazon.com. My return window had long since passed but I explained the situation to their customer service rep and he placed me on hold to talk to his supervisor about a solution for me. The call dropped-again issues on my end. But guess what? He called me back within 5 minutes. He told me that Amazon.com would allow me to return the product and credit me back the cost of the defective computer and I could then purchase something of my choosing with the funds. Five minutes after that, I had an email with the return sticker so that I could ship your lemon computer back to Amazon.com.

So, what have we learned? 1. Amazon.com cares about its customers and stands behind what it sells. 2. HP doesn't care about its customers and doesn't stand behind what it manufactures. 3. I won't be purchasing any more HP products.

HP emailed me back and wants to talk to me about these issues. Of course they can only call me between 8am and 5pm PST Monday-Friday...which is when I work...and won't be taking their call. I told them if they really want to talk to me they can call me any week night after 6pm PST.

A HUGE thank you to Amazon.com for helping me and standing behind the products they sell. A lesson all manufacturers and retailers should take note of. This is why I will continue to be a loyal amazon.com shopper.

product_title: USB 2.0 to TTL UART 6PIN Module Serial Converter CP2102
review_headline: Had to reverse RX/TX but it works fine on Windows 10 now.
review_body: I bought this to use as the serial to USB interface board for a programming cable to use with my handheld radio. An email from an expert source (Miklor.com) recommended it because it apparently isn't very finnicky about which Windows driver you have for it. It was shipped from China and reached me nearly 2 weeks ahead of the projected delivery date(!). I made the connections as directed in the Miklor article. My Windows 10 laptop downloaded a driver for it, as expected. Plugged it in, and it didn't work--wouldn't connect to my radio. As suggested by Miklor, I reversed the TX and RX connections, and it works just fine. So if you get this board to use with the Baofeng UV-5R, the connection on the board marked "RX" is actually the TX, and vice versa (at least with the cable I have). I'm happy.

1: Control Panel -> Power Options -> {Whatever Power Plant You Have Chosen] -> Change Advanced Power Settings -> USB Settings -> USB Selective Suspend Setting = Set to "Disabled"
2: Control Panel -> Power Options -> {Whatever Power Plant You Have Chosen] -> Change Advanced Power Settings -> Hard Disk -> Turn off hard disk after = set to "999999"
Hopefully this will work for you as well.

product_title: NeuTab® N7 Pro 7'' Quad Core Google Android 4.4 KitKat Tablet PC, HD 1024X600 Display, Bluetooth, Dual Camera, Google Play Pre-loaded, 3D-Game Supported (Black)
review_headline: Pretty good for the price. No customer support from NeuTab however
review_body: I purchased this model for $50 rather than the $120 that it originally retailed for. I think had the price been higher my review would be lower.  First off this is a very light tablet. I would be very concerned if I dropped it, the plastic case seems like it would shatter instantly upon impact. This can be a bonus as its small enough to fit in my back pocket without me noticing it, but on the other hand if I sat down with it still in my pocket I'm certain I'd break it. Just keep in mind that it is a very light (and presumably flimsy) tablet. This is exactly what you'd expect for a $50 tablet, however.  The screen does not perform well outdoors. Even at maximum brightness you can't see anything on the screen when outdoors. To me this is not a problem since it doesn't have any type of cell connection so I planned to use it almost exclusively indoors. Just make sure you don't have any sources of light shining directly on the screen.  The unit comes with a pretty good processor (for the price) but with only 512mb of RAM. This is the only truly negative factor with the tablet; you really have to make sure as few processes as possible are running in the background otherwise you will have some serious stability issues. A few apps crashed as I was downloading multiple updates. Had this been a more expensive tablet I might want to expect a little more.  As I said in the beginning its a pretty good tablet for the price. The one thing I would say is don't' expect to be able to play many games. A few games work but the low RAM will prevent several games from even booting up.  As far as the software itself, there is one issue that led me to return the tablet eventually. For some reason I was unable to update several Google apps on the tablet, including the "Google App for Android" app. This became a problem as the google search function was completely broken. I could search the web with Chrome but not with the Google App. Every time I attempted to update the app in the Google Play Store I received an error saying that the package was not properly signed and that I needed to uninstall and re-install the app. However, the Google App cannot be uninstalled on this device (this is not true on all Android devices and must presumably be particular to the install of Android 4.4 that NueTab puts on these tablets). I contacted NeuTab's customer support about this issue but received zero response. Had this been from a major manufacturer (Dell or Samsung, for example) I would probably give this fewer stars, but given the price I kind of expected as much. After much experimentation the only option left to me was to root the device and install a fresh version of Kitkat.  In the end I returned the tablet because if I'm going to be rooting a tablet I'd rather spend the same amount of money for a used tablet with higher system specifications, which I did.  In all, it was a decent tablet for the money, and I only returned the tablet for the reason above. Instead I ordered a used Dell Venue 7 tablet which has more storage and higher RAM (although sadly a slower processor) than this model, but is used.  If you're looking for a cheap tablet that will run email (although sadly not Google Inbox, for some reason) and web browsing, a few word processing applications and some games for $50 or less than I would recommend this tablet (presuming they fix the issue with the Google Search function). Just keep in mind that, due to its low price, you get what you pay for.

product_title: Philips BDM4065UC 40" Class 4K Monitor UHD 3840 x2160 Resolution, Speakers, USB Hub, VGA, DisplayPort, Mini DisplayPort, HDMI, MHL-HDMI
review_headline: Excellent Image Quality. Still Acclimating to Brightness.
review_body:
I've been using this monitor for over two months now and I have to admit that it is worthy of five stars. So I've upgraded my original rating from 3 stars to 4 stars and now 5 stars - even though it is not perfect. The backlight intensity appears to drop off slightly at the edges most noticeably the outside inch or so. It may be because I'm sitting too close to the monitor and the viewing angle is affecting the apparent intensity at the edges.

I was surprised that my 5 year old XFX ATI Radeon HD 5850 graphics card was able to display in full UHD resolution, but only at 24 frames per second. So I purchased a [[ASIN:B00OSS0AG4 EVGA GeForce GTX 970 FTW ACX 2.0 4GB GDDR5 256bit, DVI-I, DVI-D, HDMI, DP SLI Ready Graphics Card 04G-P4-2978-KR]] to drive this monitor. Now it displays at 60 frames per second at 4K after changing the display port setup to the latest standard, Version 1.2. Otherwise you will only get 30 frames per second.

I absolutely hate the pivoting joystick control on the backside of this monitor. I think my rocker switch is partially defective because it seems to have a mind of its own. It took nearly an hour just to set it to version 1.2. Somehow the PIP got turned on and it was next to impossible to get rid of it.

I had a 27" HP monitor prior to this 40 inch monitor, so it took over a week for me to adapt to the blinding light from a 40 inch monitor when viewing text against a white background. I tried to lower the light intensity somewhat, but the contrast didn't look right. I could not sit in front of this monitor very long - gave me me a bad headache. But now I've adapted better - still get headaches if I don't take regular breaks. Or maybe I've gradually gone blind the past month. For the first two or three weeks I really regretted not getting a 32 inch UHD monitor, but now I'm at a point of no return. This monitor can partially light up a room at night when displaying a white background image. It produces a lot of light.

Now that I've somewhat adapted to this monitor size, I find the 27 inch monitor feels small. And the 23 inch monitor I have looks simply too small. It's surprising how quickly we adapt to bigger and better things. I bought a right angle power cord to push the monitor further away from where I sit. I think Philips should have supplied a right angle cord or at least have it connect toward the bottom like most monitors do. Philips includes a full range of useless cables for this monitor and omit the one most essential cable, the Display Port cable. I can't quite imagine why anyone would spend this much money on a monitor and not use the Display Port. Nearly all the other cables they included are useless and a total waste of money. And as I've already mentioned, the power cable should have been right angle so that it can be placed closer to the wall. So even the power cable is useless because I had to purchase it separately.

My biggest concern is long term reliability. I have had very bad luck with Philips products in the past - three expensive home electronics items that all totally failed just after the warranty expired - a $2500 aggregate loss. If this monitor fails, it will be the last Philips product I ever purchase in my life. If a monitor like this had been available from a name brand reputable supplier like LG or Samsung, I'd have purchased it even for a 25% adder in price.

Now I can understand the advantage of a curved monitor. The light intensity drops off slightly as a function of the viewing angle if you are sitting close to the monitor. A curved monitor would help keep the viewing angle more perpendicular at the edges. I do a lot of accounting and comparisons, so it's advantageous to be able to do split screen. Sometimes I invert the screen color to avoid blinding myself and the resultant headaches.

I bought a [[ASIN:B00U0UXYRQ Samsung BD-J7500 3D 4K Upscaling Blu-ray Player with Wi-Fi (2015 Model)]]to watch some movies using this monitor, but I haven't set up both the Blu-ray Player and the Philips Monitor yet. I just today got the monitor software set up properly. I did preview a Blu-ray movie, but didn't have either side set up to watch in HD Upscale mode. Even so, I was suitably impressed with the movie quality. That was with the XFX Video card, however.e Blu-ray Player and the Philips Monitor yet. I just today got the monitor software set up properly. I did preview a Blu-ray movie, but didn't have either side set up to watch in HD Upscale mode. Even so, I was suitably impressed with the movie quality. That was with the XFX Video card, however.

News flash scammers: you're still cons,  criminals,  and lacking in cerebral substance...oh,  and your slightly improved English still makes you transparent. We can spot an out of use piece of vernacular faster than a cheap 128gb SD card in a sea of real ones.  Don't buy this card.  It's a fake.

review_headline: Not a bad case but needs modification
review_body:
I have mixed feeling about this case. I like the color and the material. The magnetic lock/unlock works as expected.

However the ridge/hinge is significant. Maybe that's unavoidable. It's not the end of the world.

There are two bigger problems. First, the opening for the power/dock connector is a little small and none of the cables I have fit well. A little work with a rat-tail file will address that. Second, the case rests too closely on the power switch which means that holding the case wrong can easily cause the power button to be activated, turning the iPad off at inopportune times.

Again I think this is fixable using the file/rasp but I also think both of these issues could have been addressed in the product design or represent poor construction.

product_title: iDeaUSA® 10.1” Octa Core Tablet PC, Google Android 4.4 Tablet, 1GB RAM, 16GB Nand Flash, 1024*600 Wide Display, Dual Camera, Netflix, Skype, 3D Games, Support Bluetooth HDMI - Black
review_body:
The 10" tablet market is flooded with choices, but when it comes to larger sized tablets, it's hard to find a good 7"+ tablet with decent specs. I've been using the [[ASIN:B00YE3OOLK iDeaUSA CT10 10.1" Octa Core IPS Tablet]] for the last couple days and have found it to run very smooth and has lots of customization to keep me happy.

This tablet has Android OS 4.4 KitKat and a 2GHz octa-core processor on-board (few tablets right now have such processing capacity); with that, it moves like butter and works with most all of my important apps. Google play is native and Amazon App Store was just a download to get going. I haven't found an app yet from the Amazon App Store that won't work with this tablet. Great compatibility.

Hardware-wise, the tablet features front and back cameras, approx 12GB user accessible storage and a massive 10.1" screen. There is a Micro-SD slot on the back for expandable storage. I tested the expandable storage with my [[ASIN:B005SZ4X28 SanDisk Ultra 32 GB microSDHC]] and had no issues with transfer and it being recognized.

Overall, I have found the [[ASIN:B00YE3OOLK iDeaUSA 10.1" Octa Core Tablet]] to be a very good budget grade tablet in the 7"+ range. The specs more than get the job done for most applications. This tablet is perfect for teens, adults and even children. It is great as a multi-tasker and I can't overlook that extra screen size, while still remaining extremely portable.

product_title: Acer Predator AG3-605-UR2F Gaming Desktop (Black)
review_headline: Good PC at a Good Price, but with one major problem
review_body:
Bought this PC with all the excitement of 10 year old me that couldn't afford this a long time ago. But since it got here, there was some issues that came up:

1. PC delivery was late. At least 2 weeks late. When we called Amazon to check on the status, Amazon decided that they would just send a replacement and call the previous a loss. Strange.

2: The machine RESTARTS periodically. What do I mean by that? As soon I got the PC I installed StarCraft 2, League of Legends and Deus Ex: Human Revolution. The machine handles League of Legends just fine. But when I started playing either Deus Ex or SC2, the PC would restart without warning. It happened a several times, enough for me to chat with Acer reps but they blamed it all on the system requirements of the games. I told them the PC surpasses the requirements and they did nothing else to help. To this day, I haven't played Deus Ex. Some owners of this PC blames it on the PSU saying Acer could've supplied a higher Watt PSU but thats all I can say about that.

Other than that, I would give this PC a 4/5 since its a lot better than my old laptop. I would recommended skipping this PC altogether (even though the price tag is nice) and save up for another $500-1000 machine.

product_title: Dragon Touch Y88X 7-Inch 8 GB Tablet (Black)
review_headline: Can run apps like Clash of Clans and Twitch nicely
review_body:
Needed a tablet to read PDFs in school and I can say that it got the job done.
Pros:
Can run apps like Clash of Clans and Twitch nicely. (Twitch is probably a bit more demanding than CoC)
Can be rooted.
Cons:
Not sure if its only me or also other cases, but the calibration on my tablet is off resulting in alot of annoying misclicks.
Although I say that it can run apps such as stated above, you can't really enjoy them for long periods of time due to the short life span of the battery. It dies really fast, even with only one app running in the background.
It can cause issues for certain games (School Idol Festival) because the tablet suffers the "rooted, but not rooted" issue. So you have to go through quite a deal to get this tablet to run apps that block rooted tablets/phones.
REALLY small storage, if you plan on buying this tablet you'd have to buy yourself a decent sized micro SD to compensate for the small amt of space this tablet has.

I don't think these belong in the Cons or Pros, but the speakers and camera are both below average. Although it may be a con, this is a cheap tablet so I can't really see how you'd expect high quality audio or pictures. However using earphones the audio is fine.

product_title: Kootek® Laptop Cooler Cooling Pad Fan Stand Ultra-Slim Chill Mat Master with Dual Quite Fan for 14- 15.6 inch Laptop Notebook, Apple Macbook Pro Air, Hp, Alienware, Dell, Lenovo, ASUS
review_headline: Kootek® Laptop Cooler Cooling Pad Fan
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:630a7722cdd22bedca602371acdad3]] I got this Kootek® Laptop Cooler Cooling Pad Fan Stand Ultra-Slim Chill Mat Master with Dual Quite Fan for 14- 15.6 inch Laptop for our HP laptop that we use in the living room. Now the laptop does have cool sense in it and extra fans it still gets pretty warm sitting on our laps. I got the chance to review and test this thing so I wanted to give it a try. I had purchased a laptop fan when I got the laptop..I cheaped out and got one that didnt last a week. I have been using this one well over a week now and its working great. There are 2 fans on there that have fairly large sized blades that move a lot of air. It is pretty quite too. The blue leds are cool but don't need to be there. It does add a cool factor to it though but cannot be turned off. The cord wraps up nice on the bottom too when you are not using it. That is something my other one didnt have either. Plus on the end of the plug in it has another USB port..so you don't lose a USB port when you plug this in. Nice!

All in all this has been doing great so far. It is lightweight plastic and the fan motors are pretty small but it does move some air around with the large blades. So I am giving this Kootek® Laptop Cooler Cooling Pad Fan a 5 star review and if anything changes in the course of my use I will change my review to reflect that.

If you have any questions, please feel free to ask in the comments. I will respond. If you found my review helpful, let me know. Lets keep making better buying decisions together. Thank you and as always Be Safe & Happy Shopping!!
I received a sample product to test and evaluate. If anything changes during my usage, I will update my review.

product_title: SanDisk Ultra PLUS 64GB SDXC Class 10 UHS-1 Memory Card - speed up to 40 MB/s
review_body:
GENERAL INFORMATION ABOUT SANDISK CARDS
SanDisk sells cards in various classes. Basically, the higher the class of card, the faster the SD card saves the file (anywhere from 20 MB/second to 95 MB/second). This is important if you want to take advantage of advanced camera functions such as fast action shots, continuous burst mode and multiple frames per second, and HD video (1080p). Photos are written to your card almost instantly at the higher classes so you'll get your best shot, and you’ll save time moving it all from your camera to your computer. If you use these camera functions with a lower class SD card, you may lose data and experience dropouts and stuttering.

ABOUT THIS SANDISK CLASS 10 SD CARD
This is a Class 10 SD card with write speeds of 48 MB/second. This card is great for compact-to-midrange point-and-shoot digital cameras and camcorders. I have used these cards in point and shoot cameras and game/trail cameras for the better part of a decade. I have also used some other brands. However, I've never had a SanDisk card malfunction like the other cards I've used have despite operating in below 0 degree to over 100 degrees conditions and running them through the washer/dryer. The manufacturer claims these cards are temperature proof, water proof, shock proof, and x-ray proof. These Class 10 cards are completely compatible with cameras, laptops, tablets, and other devices that support the SDHC and SDXC formats, and are capable of recording hours of HD video (1080p). These cards vary in their storage capacity (16, 32 and 64, and 128 GB).

CONCLUSION
The best thing about these cards is that they come with a lifetime limited warranty. However, I doubt that you'd ever use it. If you want quality, you can't go wrong with these SanDisk cards. I hope my review helps!

product_title: Lenovo Flex 3 Laptop
review_body: this promised to be such a great machine. purchased at costco, keyboard back light was not operational out of the box. phoned tech support, they were unable to provide any resolution. the following day, the machine went into infinite slumber. power light flashing, black screen, no response to any press of any button, no matter how long. after three hours on the line with tech support, i was given a case number. returned the machine to costco. purchased another one, exact same device. it worked for 72 hours, and failed in the exact same manner as the first. keyboard back light went out, and power button flashing while the computer remains in infinite sleep. took 90 minutes with lenovo tech support to declare this second computer a hardware failure. it, too, will be returned, and replaced with another brand. unfortunate, as i really liked the features and feel of the flex3, but two complete failures that take all your files and software with them is quite enough.  lenovo tech support was not the least bit helpful, and not clued in to the features of their own product. tech support suggested i remove the battery and see if the computer would reboot. the machine's battery is integrated. removing the battery requires removing the computer case, which, by their own policy, voids the warranty. moving on...

product_title: iDeaUSA 7 inch Quad Core Android Tablet PC, Android 4.4 System, 1GB RAM 8GB ROM, IPS Display 1024*600, Dual Camera, Bluetooth, Mini HDMI Output-Black
review_headline: This little tablet is awesome! The screen is bright and clear
review_body: This little tablet is awesome! The screen is bright and clear. The processor is quick and snappy. I haven't had any crashes or frozen screens yet. It doesn't come with a lot of bloat ware. Memory is sufficient if you just plan on using it to surf the web and do social media and what not. But it has a micro-SD slot and I suggest adding a card to it if you have a lot of music. I'm using it as a nicer replacement for a full ipod. The on board speakers are not that good. But that's to be expected on something like this. Just pair it up with a nice set of Bluetooth head phones and your good to go! Just know that this connects through WiFi not a phone service provider. That's where the micro-SD card comes in handy. Just load it up with your media while on your home network. It charges fast and the battery time is on par with my laptop. Added bonus. It has micro-HDMI port! Not many of the name brands have that let alone at this price point. Once you get a case for it remove the screen protector for better touch sensitivity. I have the iDeaUSA® 7 Windows version of this tablet as well. But I find myself using this one more often.

product_title: Linksys AC2600 4 x 4 MU-MIMO Dual-Band Gigabit Router with USB 3.0 and eSATA (EA8500)
review_body: Edit 1:  This EA8500 is one month old and still stable as a rock, super fast speeds, no dead wifi spots at all like most other routers form other manufactures.  I found the system info page that tells us what connection rate and a hole lot more You just refresh it to get an update, not as fancy as other router brands but it does show more than any GUI in other routers.  http://192.168.1.1/sysinfo.cgi  A little background, I had d-link, Netgear, apple, all were good except for Netgear had to reboot weekly to monthly, then RT-AC66R - this was a good Asus router, I had the RT-AC68R - this was good at 2.4GHz but 5GHz sucked in range so 5GHz usability was useless and it had awful USB support (problems).  Now the Asus RT-AC87R (I am going to reference it as 87r, I owned that for 1 year), where to begin….  I thought the 87r would be my router for years (boy was I wrong)…  The 5GHz covered all my house inside, BUT, areas where I put my phone, (to do wifi to hardwired device remote control) just gave me constant problems, some days after a new firmware it seemed to work (sometimes) and I thought finally, then some day or days later BAM not working in those areas again. (Now before you think or say something, all I did was change to the Linksys router, NOTHING ELSE, more on that below).  The best I ever achieved from the 87r was about maybe a month with a firmware, before something went wrong, lag, wifi drops, etc.. I totally gave up on USB drives connected through it, now I have a NAS (Best purchase I have made in years)  Onto my new Linksys EA8500, in my case, this is my first Linksys router I have ever owned.  First what I read on it….  - I read the web GUI was slow by some, I find it supper fast, I have no idea why others complain about that at all.  - Wifi range, well the Linksys is the same as the 87R with 2.4 GHz range (outstanding), and noticeably better than the 87r on the 5GHz band.  - I read of a few having some kind of power down after 6 hours or so, I havenever seen this at all (the latest firmware update address this anyway for the ones with tis issue).  Now my findings  Good  -Absolutely no dead wifi spots with the Linksys, super fast connection from my wifi app to wired lan control device.  I can't find any WiFi dead spots in my house with this Linksys router on 5 GHz or 2.4GHz. (As I have had with the 87r, especially with my remote app)  - I have an app on my phone that connects to a hardwired device, on the 87r this was so bad and useless that the original (old) app no longer functioned and I had to buy a different app to get it to work, I no longer have my phone wifi to hardwired device control problems at all, both apps work great on the Linksys EA8500 and I checked for the latest update on the first app that went wonky on the 87r and it was not updated for 30+ days.  - I no longer have any lag (tho dd-wrt firmware on the 87r removed it usually all the time, but it came back after days on the 87r).  My online gaming with Asus routers on Monday night’s were all horrible, so bad that I usually shut down my PS4.  Now with the EA8500 my lag is very minimal.  - Setup was simple, but I did do some reading into this before hand, so I knew what to tweak to get great performance out of the Linksys.  - I did have a HP wifi printer problem, FIXED I had to reset my network settings in my HP printer (nothing with the router at all).  - My download speeds since I installed the EA8500 are my best ever.  Any router before (including the rt-ac87r) I got a max of 30-32 down, now with the Linksys I always see 34-35.  -I have adjusted some things in the settings and unlike the 87r, no firmware degradation at all...... Meaning every time I rebooted (I owned 2 87r’s, first one died due to overheating) the 87r would perform worse and worse (more problems, etc..)after every reboot, no matter what firmware I used, until I flushed the ac87r and started from scratch again, it happened with both 87r’s, I have complained about thisfrom time to time with Asus and they did not care.  Nothing at all like this on the Linksys, the Linksys just works like it should and rebooting does nothing bad at all to it.  - NO WiFi drops with the Linksys on either band, the Linksys just works and works perfectly.  - Web page refreshes on wifi devices are the same as my Asus 87r (when it was working good)  - I use and love the way QOS is used on the linksys (I hated the Asus way, tried it, never worked for me and turned it off).  I see no speed degrade with QOS on, my ps4 also has very little lag, that's my priority in the QOS for me, so QOS in this router works.  - Linksys support is very great and responsive (from the printer issue I had, they gave me things to try on my Printer problem that turned out to be resettings network settings on the printer).  - DHCP reservation is super easy on the Linksys, you click on “Network Map” and all of your connected devices are showing, just click a device and add DHCP reservation, it’s that easy.  Linksys and I also recommends you do this, as some devices get confused (on any router)  Bad (if you call it bad)  - The IOS app to configure the router does not work with IOS 9 beta yet, expected as it is a beta IOS, it does work from my android note 10.1 version 1 perfectly. (I use the web GUI anyway, but I don't have to go into that often at all due to the Linksys just working).  - I have no idea what my wifi connections are at ( meaning 100, 300, 400, or 800), Asus and dd-wrt gave me this info, nowhere found on the Linksys. (This would be my only wish, but not needed)  - I don’t have lights up front and I like that, I do have a Linksys light on top that is steady when connected to my ISP and flashing when not, I do like this.  - I do not like the fact I only get 90 days telephone support, but with quick e-mail and forum support, it’s not needed.  - Pricy but performance and stability is worth the price (I paid more for my Asus rt-ac87r a year before and that was nothing but problems and stuff not working the entire year, yah it has more bells and whistles but at slower speeds and very unstable hardware and firmware)  Summery I don't have absolutely nothing bad to say or found about this router, I keep looking for something, not performing properly, but everything I do with the Linksys = it just works perfectly, to date.  If you are looking for tons of things to tweak, bloatware (I call it, you may not), love to reboot and have unstable hardware = look elsewhere, BUT if you are looking for a router with all the features needed and for a router that is stable as a rock = Look no further this EA8500 is the one!  So far I love this Linksys Router  If this stays like this, I have the best router made to date! This is how a router should work, perfectly. NOT half baked!!

product_title: Novastor 6CMCRPCHL NOVABACKUP CENTRAL MANAGEMENT CONSOLE - NOVACARE PREMIUM - 1 YEAR PROTECTION
review_body:
The story starts in 2014.

I bought the NovaStor backup system for my laptop, a high end Toshiba widescreen. My order was placed at a particularly busy time in my business cycle and so I did not rush to install the software. I activated it, decided that the instructions were not clearly written and that I did not have time to work on it just then.

When I did try to work through the backup process, I found that the buttons on the main work screen popup are all below the bottom of my laptop display. There is no scroll bar on the right side and the software is unusable. So I wrote to NovaStor's support people.

The first email I received from NovaStor support had no relationship at all to the problem at hand – nothing at all. Even better, though, I received a "case closed how did we do?" email survey before I received the whacky support letter.

I replied to NovaStor support and also to the survey saying that my problem was not solved. When the reply came, the technician said that there is no way to use the software without resizing the laptop display. That's it. Think about rebooting 4 times a day to do 2 backups.

I applied for a refund for this unusable software but my request was denied because it had been over 30 days since my purchase. The Customer Service Dude was rude because I dared to ask for a refund outside of the warranty period.

Why waste your time with an arrogant company that can't produce a usable interface?

2015 Update.

My computer crashed and when I tried to reinstall Novastor, I found that the serial number was "disabled". I contacted Novastor to get a new serial number password or other workaround. The customer service department is rude and uninformed, wasting weeks of my time before sending me to another department that told me I had to buy a completely new installation.

product_title: Samsung 850 EVO Parent
review_body: This was perfect!! Have a Dell N5110, very slow, unusable slow. No virus' or malware just painfully slow. Installed this and BAM!! runs like my 2014 Macbook Air. Very fast boot, very fast program load. All and all most bang for buck upgrade I have ever done to a computer. I will never be without an SSD again. My install required a complete disassembly down to motherboard but most laptops aren't that poorly built, easy to change out. Samsung even sends migration software with this drive. I simply new SSD up with and adapter to USB and used included software to clone my old drive to new one. Then installed new drive in laptop, booted and used Samsung software to optimize. Very easy, solid software kudos Samsung. Now to see how long it lasts. I'm sure everything will be fine.

product_title: SanDisk 16GB SDHC Card Class 4 Secure Digital High Capacity - Bulk Packaging
review_body:
GENERAL INFORMATION ABOUT SANDISK CARDS
SanDisk sells cards in various classes. Basically, the higher the class of card, the faster the SD card saves the file (anywhere from 20 MB/second to 95 MB/second). This is important if you want to take advantage of advanced camera functions such as fast action shots, continuous burst mode and multiple frames per second, and HD video (1080p). Photos are written to your card almost instantly at the higher classes so you'll get your best shot, and you’ll save time moving it all from your camera to your computer. If you use these camera functions with a lower class SD card, you may lose data and experience dropouts and stuttering.

ABOUT THIS SANDISK CLASS 4 SD CARDS
This is a standard Class 4 SD card with write speeds of 20 MB/second. Unless you take advantage of high end camera functions, you won't need a higher class (i.e. more expensive) card. I have used these cards in point and shoot cameras and game/trail cameras for the better part of a decade. I have also used some other brands. However, I've never had a SanDisk card malfunction like the other cards I've used have despite operating in below 0 degree to over 100 degrees conditions (rated to operate in conditions between -13 and 185 degrees) and running them through the washer/dryer. These standard Class 4 cards are completely compatible with cameras, laptops, tablets, and other devices that support the SDHC and SDXC formats, and are capable of recording hours of HD video (720p). These cards vary in their storage capacity (2, 4, 8, 16, 32 and 64 GB).

CONCLUSION
The best thing about these cards is that they come with a 5-year warranty. However, I doubt that you'd ever use it. If you want quality, you can't go wrong with these SanDisk cards. I hope my review helps!

product_title: KHOMO Brown Book Style Leather Case for Amazon Kindle Voyage
review_headline: Essential for all Kindle Voyage owners!!!
review_body:
All the old Kindle models had a matte-finished grey plastic bezel and backside that mysteriously rejected human fingerprints. The new Kindle Voyage and Kindle Paperwhite models have a glassy black bezel and backside that shows the slightest smudge - really dumb change for a HANDHELD, TOUCHSCREEN device!!! Even dumber is that most available cases for these devices expose the whole bezel, including the natural spots for holding its. This product is a smart purchase for every Voyage owner. It covers all the places you could possibly touch the bezel.
You don't even have to touch the page-turn sensors since the flexible faux-leather does that just fine. product_title: BATTOP Slim Wireless Bluetooth Keyboard with Multi-Touchpad Built-In Unique Autoshrink Hidden Stands for Windows, Android 4.0 and Above System Tablet/PC/ Smart Phone-Black
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:c1e46f5085084a19c663bff46861eaa6]]Occasionally, some gadget comes along that I didn't really expect to wow me and then it does. This keyboard is one of those items. I have several Bluetooth keyboards but this one is different. This keyboard really has everything that I have been looking for in a keyboard.

This keyboard is a little over 10 inches wide. I have a 10 inch tablet that sits on it perfectly. The tablet is very thin and light weight. This is really nice whn I take it with me. The keyboard is Bluetooth and I had no trouble getting it to connect to my tablets. When I pressed the connect button on the keyboard and pair on my tablet, a popup on the tablet asked me to enter a code on the tablet screen. As soon as I entered the code, the tablet started working.

The keyboard is very responsive to touch. There is no lag time when pressing keys. With this keyboard, I can type quickly without making a lot of mistakes. There are two features of this keyboard that I really love and that really sold me on this keyboard. First, there are two small legs/props that can be hidden inside the keyboard but pop out to use as a prop for the tablet. My 10 inch tablet sets here very securely but my 7 inch also fits. When using the keyboard with a tablet, it's like having a small laptop. The second thing I really love about this keyboard, is the touchpad. It works great and let's me use the keyboard to move around the screen instead of having to use a separate mouse or touching the screen. I am used to using a laptop a lot so I use a touchpad all the time. It is smaller than a standard keyboard but it feels very comfortable with the touchpad and the way the keys feel.

There are a lot of extra "functions" on the this keyboard. There is an option to turn off the touchpad. There is also a Function num lock so that you can actually create a number keypad with some of the letter keys. This is nice if you just need the the numbers so that they are in the same order as a regular number keypad. You can use the keyboard to control volume, to pause and play music or videos, etc... The keybaord really offers a ot of the same things that a full size keyboard would offer.

So far I am happy with this keyboard. It has worked with well each tablet I have tried it with. The battery life of this keyboard is very impressive. It will stay charged for 24-30 hours when being used. I don't use it for that many straight hours so the keyboard lasts for days and days. This is definitely an A+ item.

product_title: Acer Aspire V17 Nitro Black Edition VN7-791G-76Z8 17.3-Inch Full HD (1920 x 1080) Gaming Laptop
review_body:
Many aspects of this laptop aren't too bad. The price is very good for the performance. However, some huge downsides:
-Comes with a s***ton of bloatware from Acer. It took me at least an hour to figure out what to throw away and what to keep. What could I delete without gimping the computer? It's not very clear.
-However, I found out the bloatware runs even deeper. Need to upgrade your Intel Drivers? Gotta use the Acer drivers! Drivers which many games don't seem to recognize.
-RAM upgradability. You can't upgrade your RAM without a technician apparently. This is a problem for me; I live in Japan so I can't exactly go to Walmart.
-Hard disk upgradability. The s***ty hard disk read speeds are the biggest problem with this laptop. I thought I could simply switch out the hard drive for a better one, but this is quite annoying as they don't provide the laptop with a backup OEM Windows CD.

The hard disk upgradability is a major concern for me especially because, just a few weeks after using this laptop, I get some random periodic slowdowns. Every 10 minutes or so, there's a 1 second program freeze (including games of course); my guess would be that its trying to access the hard drive but cannot go quickly enough, but it might be some of their integrated bloatware too. r

It was pretty hard to find information about any of this. Most websites only review performance (which this laptop is not halfway bad at). But Acer are being dicks with bloatware. It's a real shame in light of things like the amazing quality screen, good performance and good price.

product_title: TP-Link AC2300 Wireless WiFi Router | Powerful 1.8GHz Dual-Core Processor | 802.11ac Wave 2 MU-MIMO (Archer C2300)
review_headline: Just buy it.  It works.  It's simple.  It's solid.
review_body:
I'm quickly becoming a very bit TP-Link fan. When balancing cost and quality, I've found their equipment to be really good. Not perfect - but good enough and quickly getting better. For this purchase I need a fairly basic router with simple software that just about anyone could configure. It needed to be a solid performer that "just worked". So far, it's been running like a champ.

Previously I'd had a D-Link that was about 4-5 years old in it's place. That router did an admirable job but it didn't quite have the "umpf!" to push out that signal as far as I needed it to. It had all internal antennas, so with this new purchase I knew I wanted something external. This model has 3 external antennas and the signal strength is very good.

I plugged it in and it started working immediately. One critical point I have is that when it turns on, it doesn't have your standard "admin/admin" username and password. The instructions don't really point that out very clearly. What I was able to do was use "admin" as a username and then, on the back of the router, you'll find a series of numbers that represents the default pin for that device. Type those numbers in as the password and you're good to go to configure it.

Anyway, it's a solid performer. Hasn't missed a beat since it was set up. It's signal is strong enough now that I didn't need to use a WiFi extender I had plugged in halfway across the house. That doesn't mean it's going to blast wifi everywhere you want it, but in my case and in the configuration for my home, it has worked wonderfully.

product_title: Taotronics
review_headline: One of the best out there period!
review_body:
One of the best out there period!

Led:
- Led color is great and highly customizable.
- Size of the lamp is is HUGE compared to other lamps. At about 7 inches diagonally, it really looks like a tablet!
- I didn't need the night light feature but now I seem to use it all the time to find my glasses or walk to the bathroom at night.

Features:
- Vibrates!!! when you get to the max brightness or at the end of the warm or cool light color. This is a great feature not found on other lamps.
- USB is handy too. Now I don't have to use my iphone power adapter. I can use a single outlet vs 2.

Build quality:
- Quality plastic with a heavy tempered glass base. The base is very pretty with the power symbol staying lit up.
- The led head has an aluminum top to dissipate heat although it does not get hot at all. I do wish the arm was metal but the plastic is very sturdy.
- At an extreme angle, the light does topple but no one would use it with the arm extended out so far. It is adjustable to anyone's needs.

I can't think of any cons other than the arm not being metal but this is being too picky. After receiving this to test, I highly recommend this product. It is definitely the best taotronics lamp so far.

product_title: ASUS MG24UQ 23.6" IPS 4K 4ms HDMI DP Ergonomic Adaptive-Sync Gaming Monitor
review_headline: Great 144Hz 1440p monitor with a light AG coating
review_body:
Great 144Hz 1440p monitor with a light AG coating. I have a Nvidia GPU but I wasn't interested in spending $200 more for the same panel. 144Hz with fixed refresh rate is good enough for me.

Contrast ratio is much higher than my Dell U2312HM at the same brightness. Response times are very good when using TraceFree at 80, though still falls short of a 144Hz TN monitor. Color and gamma are largely stable as expected but due to glow at off angles, viewing it dead on still provides the best experience.

Issues with IPS glow on the edges, but it's only apparent in a dark room viewing dark content. I play with the lights on so it doesn't bother me that much. Backlight bleed is acceptable, not the best I've seen but not the worst either. No dead pixels or smudges observed, but I haven't combed the monitor with a magnifying glass.

Text was slightly blurry out of the box almost as if it had a shadow around it. At first I thought it was cleartype not being calibrated but I eventually tracked it down to the VividPixel setting. At 25, it adds a slight blur to black text on light background. Setting it to 0 resolves the issue.

product_title: SROCKER M302 Ultra-thin Wireless Bluetooth 3.0 Rechargeable Silent Click Optical Mouse/Mice with 4 Buttons and Built-in 830mAh Battery for All Bluetooth Devices
review_headline: Difference Between 2.4GHz Wireless & Bluetooth - Smooth Tracking, Extremely Quiet Clicking
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:84a05fc1da342918f1bcbd1eeb7fa4ef]]Just to help make life generally easier - there is an absolute distinction between \\"2.4GHz Wireless\\" and \\"Bluetooth\\".

If you see something that says \\"2.4GHz Wireless\\" (and as long as the product description is actually correct...), it will have a Plug-In Dongle. Usually plug-in-play, and normally a Type A USB head (never actually seen a micro USB wireless dongle though).

If it says \\"Bluetooth\\", then no dongle will be found. You pair it up like you would any other Bluetooth device. Turn it on, scan for it on the hosting computer, pair, and done.

This one is a Bluetooth mouse, and paired fine with an Acer and a Samsung Galaxy S6 (that was odd, seeing a mouse cursor on my smartphone ((lol)) ).

Unlike prior \\"slim mouse\\" designs I have used, where the edges were a bit too pointed, the edges on this one is more rounded, and thereby more comfortable to hole with a full grasp. Very smooth tracking across a hard speed mat. And, yes, an on/off button. You may be surprised how many Bluetooth peripherals don't have one.

And yes, this is an absolutely QUIET mouse clicker. Does have decent tactile response to the buttons and mouse wheel although a little shallow in the snap.

- Complimentary product provided for evaluation, yet my thinking here reflects all my personal purchasing decision processes, and hopefully may help clarify if this best meets your own needs and expectations.

If you look on the inside of them, they even have real screws holding these things together. Well, mine literally fell apart tonight when I picked them up. Guess what?!? Those screws that you see are not screws. It is just a cheap plastic trick to make you think you have a quality product. Those screws are not actually screws. It is just an outer appearance...unbelievable. How much did Logitech actually save by engineering in fake screws into the plastics vs. actually just placing in screws into the headset? I have used Logitech for many years but no more.

product_title: Fire HD 6
review_body:
I bought the 16 GB version for my 5-year-old and opted out of the "kids" version because it was $50 cheaper. I ended up getting the warranty anyway ($25) and didn't know if we wanted a FreeTime subscription, so with my existing Prime membership and a free one-month trial we would only save $8 by buying the kids version IF we decide to keep the FreeTime subscription for a year. We also didn't get the foam "buffer" with the non-kids version but I don't feel it's necessary. Besides occasionally dropping the tablet my daughter treats her tab with care, like we've taught her to do with everything else, and there's a no-questions warranty besides. And EVEN THEN this thing is built pretty damn tough.

I really like this thing. I'm not certain I would like it for myself (I prefer vanilla Android, rooting and SU privileges - not being restricted to the Amazon eco-system) but this thing is PERFECT for kids, especially young ones. Setting up an account for her, adding apps, and setting usage restriction were all very easy to do and understand. FreeTime allows her access to books (which she loves), kids-specific apps which she can add and delete at will, and generally let's her have a tab customized just for her. She's used to using other cheap (sub-$100) tablets, an iPod, and the PC so this thing is extremely user-friendly for her. The ability to set late-evening/early-morning and time restrictions, allowing her "game time" only after earning credits, and all of the user-restrictions are very well thought out.

Battery-life, display quality, and pretty much everything else about this tab is more than perfect. Especially for it's price-range.

What I don't like are the adds on the home screen (it's tacky and reminds me that this is Amazon's world - we only live in it) which you can pay an extra $16 (I believe) to have removed. Again, this tablet doesn't suit me (or probably my pre-teen) who prefers the freedom ofa stock OS but for young kids or people who prefer their OS more "user-friendly" but locked down and catered to their needs (e.g. Apple users or grandparents) then this tab is perfect.

TL;DR - Great for kids and less tech-savvy users, to restrictive for more advanced users. Great quality product especially for the price.

product_title: Microsoft Sculpt Ergonomic Mouse (L6V-00001)
review_body:
My last mouse, also a Microsoft, was far more "ergonomic" looking, but it had its own quirks. The mouse wheel was hard to click, the receiver sometimes needed to be disconnected and reconnected, and the rubber on the thumb rest started coming off. Once I wore out the switch under the left-click button, it was time to upgrade. This mouse does not look so ergonomic, but it falls naturally into the palm and works even better than the mouse it replaced. The blue start menu button will not see much use, but the back button is beneath it and for now, is a little unfamiliar to work with. It is, however, protected beneath the rubber and takes a small effort to push, whereas the fore/back buttons on the old mouse protruded a little too much and I was accidentally hitting them with my hand.

I am now tempted to get the matching Sculpt keyboard, as it seems to be the only remaining split ergonomic wireless keyboard Microsoft offers. They make a nice looking set.

product_title: Case Logic VNB-217 Value 17-Inch Laptop Backpack (Black)
review_headline: Fits a 17.3" gaming laptop, plus accessories with ease! And on a budget!
review_body:
Just bought a large gaming laptop, and this fits perfectly. For reference, my laptop is a ASUS ROG G751JT-CH71 17.3". Plenty of room for laptop, the huge AC adapter/power supply, large "can style" headphones, mouse, and mouse pad.

The only time I bring my laptop anywhere is occasionally to a friend's house. If I were in college, or (for some reason) bringing this thing to work every day, I would probably want a bag with considerably more padding. But I didn't want to spend a ton of money on a backpack that wasn't going to get used frequently.

Seems like decent quality. I've never had a problem with Case Logic products, having used them since the 90's with CD storage books. I can't imagine you could find a better padded backpack for 17.3" laptops at this price.

product_title: Leather Vintage Rustic Crossbody Messenger Courier Satchel Bag Gift Men Women
review_headline: Very small, very cheap, decent looking bag
review_body:
When my girlfriend saw this bag, she commented, "Ok, that one is cute!" While this alone wouldn't detract me from liking it, it really is very small. Once my 13" Macbook Pro is placed in this bag, there's maybe room for another notebook or small textbook.

Otherwise, it's ok. You should recognize you're getting only $50 or so of leather bag...which is not a lot of leather bag. The hardware, leather, etc is all noticeably cheap, and it's very easy to spot the cut corners. The leather is quite stiff for how thin it is, possibly because of the lining. The look of the bag isn't too bad, though, so if you're looking for a cheap, decent looking bag that won't last too long or carry much at all, this may be worth it to you.

Part of me thinks this deserves 4 stars for a product that roughly meets expectation for the price point, but I do want to emphasize that this isn't a high-quality product. Amazon does identify 3 stars as "It's okay," so we'll go with it.

2.13.16 Update: I just noticed this is the most "unhelpful" voted review I've ever written. I checked, and sure enough, at time of writing, every single negative review on this bag older than a month has 19-20 unhelpful votes. Perhaps "RusticTown" (the seller) is about 20 employees strong? If you are reading this and sincerely feel this review isn't helpful, feel free to leave a comment with some feedback.

product_title: Patriot LX Series 256GB High Speed Micro SDXC Class 10 UHS-1 Transfer Speeds For Action Cameras, Phones, Tablets, and PCs
review_headline: Large and in charge, and it should work in *any phone* that uses the Ex-FAT file system...
review_body:
I opted for this particular 128GB MicroSDXC card because of the specifications. So far, not bad at all.

I upgraded from a 64GB A-Data card, and this one is much quicker.

I am working towards a goal of having every song I've ever liked over the course of my entire life (several decades) on my phone. Cool, huh?

In addition to my "regular collection" being on the card, it's providing me ample space to pursue the aforementioned goal.

This is 100% working in my Samsung Galaxy Note 3, and I'm told it should work in ANY device that supports the ExFAT file system (all Samsung Galaxy devices that accommodate a MicroSD card included)

Samsung says the Note 3 supports up to a 64GB card. It supports a 64GB, it also supports a 128GB, and it will probably support SanDisk's 200GB, too.

I had been waiting patiently for the price on these to drop to around $50, and it did, so I pulled the trigger on it. I'm really glad that I did.

Now, to wait for SanDisk to release something ELSE huge - bigger than the 200GB (not 256GB???) that they have out now, so the 200GB card will drop, hopefully, to $50. Release a 512GB MicroSD already.

Isn't it absolutely amazing how 128GB of memory is stored inside this tiny little memory card? Technology is amazing.

Do it. Buy it. Please and thanks.

review_body:
My son recently turned 6 and for his birthday I got him this tablet to play a few learning games and to watch Netflix on. For a first tablet I would have to say it's definitely worth what I paid (less than $60).

The camera quality on this tablet is poor but my 6 year old doesn't take pictures so this is fine with me. It's very easy to use with a simple on and off button so my son can easily shut it off when I tell him to.

If you are looking for a simple tablet for your child this is a great one. Once he gets older I may splurge on a better one but I couldn't beat the price for this one.

product_title: Cooler Master Hyper Compact CPU Cooler with Dual Looped Direct Contact Heatpipes
review_body: Had problems with my PC freezing up I had to restart my computer time and time again because of overheating found out that my processor was getting too hot. I have a AMD octa core 8350 processor the original stock CPU fan cooler. I checked out several options on different CPU fan coolers some water coolers which I didn't want to try risking damage to my motherboard or any other components. So I did my research on this v8 Cooler Master it had good reviews even on YouTube. So I decided to take the risk and give it a shot and boy I'm glad I did my CPU now runs about 50% cooler than before and it doesn't shut down when trying to compress videos or gaming that was one of my biggest issues but now it's faster and it doesn't overheat at all. It's a little bulky in size but if you have the room it would be no problem at all, I have a mid size tower and it fit perfect. I would highly recommend this product for anyone who has multiple core processors does a lot of HD video compression  or lots of high graphics gaming. I'm quite sure that there are better CPU coolers out there but this one has my vote hands down.

product_title: Power Supply+Cord for Dell 09RN2C 0HN662 0TR82J 1XRN1 6TFFF 6TM1C 9RN2C A065R039L AA65NM121 CN-0928G4 CN-0K9TGR DA65NM111-00 DA65NS3-00 FA45NE1-00 HA65NM130 LA65NE1-01 PA-1650-02D2 PA-1650-02DD

product_title: Anker Folio Keyboard Case Bluetooth for iPad 4 / 3 / 2 [ONLY] with 6-Month Battery Life Between Charges and Comfortable Low-Profile Keys
review_headline: this Anker Bluetooth folio keyboard will work fine so long you are not typing in a quiet ...
review_body:
For folks who simply needs to convert their iPad to a desktop computer, this Anker Bluetooth folio keyboard will work fine so long you are not typing in a quiet space near someone taking a nap. The good: sturdy construction, good layout and responsive keys, strong magnet that holds the iPad steady when typing, connects easily with the iPad, strong holders provided to retain the iPad, nice faux leather and grey felt on the inside and cover shuts off the iPad screen when closed. The keyboard is responsive and keys have good tension feedback by supportive springs. For the short duration I tried the keyboard folio, I had no battery problem. The unit worked right out of the box and charged without issue. The bad: works in only one position--desktop landscape with no angle adjustments and no portrait position use. In folio closed position there is no magnet holder or snaps or anything else that will hold the folio closed, which could be resolved by adding strong magnets outside of the iPad holder brackets. Like the IOS software keyboard no escape key is provided-function key and home key combo may be an option (I forgot to try it). Cover captures fingerprints easily, but cleans easily. The keyboard keys cannot operate quietly.

Had it not been for the one position operation mode provided, I would have overlook all other points listed as bad. The iPad is too versatile to have the keyboard operate in on position only. When operating the iPad and keyboard on my knees, another screen angle is required.

review_body:
Very straightforward router to set-up and install. I have Macs, so could not use the installation CD provided (it's a mini-CD that can't be loaded into the CD drives on my laptop/desktop). That said, it was still easy to go online to TP-Link's website and download the driver software update and then complete the set-up through a web-browser.

Signal strength is good for what I need, even with the router hidden away inside a very solid-wood secretary desk. No issues with random restarts or spotty connections so far.

There are also iPhone and Android apps for setting up and managing the router, which look pretty nice (although I haven't had to use it much so far since everything has been working well). product_title: TRENDnet USB 2.0 to 10/100 Fast Ethernet LAN Wired Network Adapter for Macbook, Chromebook, Windows 8.1 and Earlier, Wii, Wii U, Linux, and Specific Android Tablets, ASIX AX88772A Chipset, TU2-ET100
review_headline: It works well with the Surface 3 Pro
review_body: Got this to pair with my Surface 3 Pro to provide a wired connection alternative when WiFi isn't available (or best). It was truly plug-and-play, kind of refreshing. The normal connection when at my desk is through the wired Ethernet port on the docking station. When I tested this the first time, the Surface was still in the docking station. I unplugged the cable from the docking station and plugged it into this adapter. The system connected immediately without any issues even while still in the docking station. As with any USB device, having it connected does shorten battery life, but it's not oppressive. The Surface 3 Pro (now on Windows 10) has pretty decent battery life for such a small machine, and plugging in anything does make a pretty significant difference. Adding this isn't a bad as using an external display with an extended desktop, and there's still more than enough endurance for a 2-hour teleconference with both of those plus a USB hub and video teleconference camera/speakerphone.

If I am browsing the web and don't need my keyboard much, like when I am shopping on Amazon, I flip the keyboard under and it becomes a nice sized tablet with a stand. I was concerned about the keyboard having buttons pushed if I didn't set it on a flat surface, (usually I sit on the couch and the keyboard rests on my lap). But they keyboard is disabled as soon as you flip it under. If you are used to a nice windows computer and want something that feels more substantial than the traditional, less expensive Chromebooks, this is the one for you.

product_title: Enterprise Capacity
review_headline: Performs very well on E-SATA and USB 3.0.
review_body: I got 3 drives for my computer. I wanted 1 internal one and 2 externals for backups. The transfer rate is good. I'm able to get at least 6.4GB per minute using my external USB 3.0 cases with the drive in them. My cases will also handle E-SATA and I was able to get about 5GB. The internal drive is connect internally in the computer on a SATA II or it may be an SATA III port. I do not have them connected to an SATA 6 port yet. I'll do that when I get some sited help being I can't see. Then rerun my backup copy to se how much difference there is. I'm not expecting a lot of difference.

review_body:
This item is very likely one of the many FAKEs being sold out there. Data moved onto it quickly disappears and gets corrupted. Running the well-known H2Testw flash testing program on it generates

"The media is likely to be defective.
7.7 GByte OK (16354393 sectors)
117.1 GByte DATA LOST (245597095 sectors)"

In other words, an 8gb card being sold as a 128gb card for $70!

I am returning for money back. Don't waste your time.
Read about this phenomenon here: https://www.thecounterfeitreport.com/product/504/micro-SDXC-Memory-Cards.html

product_title: TP-Link AC2300 Wireless WiFi Router | Powerful 1.8GHz Dual-Core Processor | 802.11ac Wave 2 MU-MIMO (Archer C2300)
review_headline: Good router but with a useless DHCP Reservation Table
review_body:
Addendum 9/15/15: TP-Link issued a new beta version of the firmware dated 21050911 today. Unfortunately, it also has a defective DHCP reservation system that renders the router useless if DHCP reservations are enabled.

Pros: This router has significantly better performance than the 7 year-old D-Link DIR-655 that it replaced. It has better range but not to the degree that I could remove the additional access point on the opposite corner of my home. The webpage interface and the Android device interface app are both easy to use and reasonably comprehensive.
Cons: My biggest problem is that I had a 16-device DHCP reservation table on my DIR-655 that I could not reinstitute on the Archer C9, as doing so caused the DHCP process to become inoperable. I had to settle for manually readdressing the devices that required a fixed hardwired IP address outside of the range of the dynamic DHCP address range. I then let the computers on the LAN get dynamic addressing via DHCP. When I want to locate their IP address, I have to go to the router's DHCP table. I still have the potential problem of an address conflict among these computers if one has been asleep and finds that its address has been reassigned when waking. This is a particular problem with laptops which might be carried around to different networks where that have to have dynamic addressing capability, and thus cannot be assigned a fixed address. I contacted TP-Link Support via email but have yet to hear back from them. The router has the latest firmware (4.0.0 - 20150811).

I tried changing hdmi cables and computer settings to see if it was just going off from either of those - but the problem persisted.

Weeks later, the monitor flickers off every fifteen minutes or so - making it impossible to work on. If at all possible, buy a different monitor than this one. review_headline: Great little Windows tablet for my camping trips
review_body:
This is a great little Windows tablet! I got it to take camping with me, and I am very happy with the device so far. I think it is perfect for my backpack and camping gear. It doesn't weigh much and I can watch movies, read, listen to music, and write on Word while in my tent after a long hike or kayaking. I also got a solar charger so I can keep it charged for my longer trips.

I am using my HP Stream 7 as an extension of my home desktop. I wanted something with Windows so I can move my files and media easily. I also installed iTunes (for Windows) and moved my music and some movies onto the tablet. Works great! Nice for watching a movie in my tent! I didn't notice any issues. The screen is VERY crisp - excellent for watching movies, sound is great with ear phones or plug-in speaker, and it runs very fast. The mono speaker is fine. No issues so far - excellent value.

product_title: TP-Link N600 Wireless Dual Band PCI-Express Adapter
review_headline: Been a year, still works like new.
review_body: I bought the TP-Link TL-WDN3200 N600 about a year ago and this adapter as exceeded my expectations. It has been working pretty much every day since I got it from afternoon to night during school days and morning to night on breaks. I play many online games like OSU!, MOBAs, MMOs (not much of a FPS fan) and stream a ton of anime. My PC is not that far from the router, I live in a one story house with my room located about maybe 13 yards away, so I can see if the signal strength can be an issue to some. I get around 50-60% signal strength daily. I have compared my Netgear N600 WNDA3100 dual band adapter to the TP-Link one and surprisingly enough, the TP-Link gave me a better speed and connection with about 2.4mb/s while the former gave me about 1.2mb/s on multiple tests throughout a couple weeks. Overall, this product was an amazing buy because a year ago I needed a cheap wireless adapter that could handle online play and stream anime all at once for my budget pc build and I am currently using it as I write this review, about a year later after purchase. I have used this adapter with Windows 8, 8.1, and 10!

product_title: Kensington Orbit Trackball Mouse with Scroll Ring (K72337US)
review_headline: Figure out drag and drop and you're good to go. Works out of the box for Ubuntu 15.04
review_body:
Solved my problem. New laptop, touchpad was interfering with typing. I bought an optical mouse at Microcenter. Made the mistake of buying a cheap mouse. I went there specifically thinking trackball but came back with a cheap optical mouse. Decided to go with this device because it's well rated. Ordered it. Received within a few days with standard shipping.

Plugged it in using Ubuntu 15.04 no problem. I did not anticipate the adjustment required for drag and drop. I'm left handed. After switching the buttons I can click and hold my primary mouse button, drag and drop, no prob. I did spend some time looking for an app to provide click to drag because system mouse settings do not provide it. I found that switching the mouse buttons makes it easy to hold down the primary button and drag back and forth, up and down to my heart's content then release the button when I get to where I want to be.

I actually like drag and drop with the trackball more than the mouse now that I've used it a bit because with a mouse you're still holding the mouse when you release the button which can incur additional unintended movement. With the trackball, once you lift your finger off the ball the cursor stays put.

The scrollring is awesome. With a 13" laptop there are concessions with the keyboard that required a function key to scroll with the keyboard. The cheap optical mouse had a scrollwheel which was tedious to use. The scrollring on the trackball is precise, zippy and easy to use.

I was thinking I might be missing something with two buttons instead of three but a third button to paste doesn't matter. With my setup I can select text with the trackball, release my primary button, click again and drag to a new location while holding the button, release to paste text at the cursor location. Most likely drag and drop 101 but I'm very pleased.

I decided on the wired trackball because any device, wireless or not, will occupy a usb port. My conclusion is, can't beat it for the money. Great value. Does everything I need it to straight out of the box. I hope my review saves someone else who may be moving over to a trackball some of the time I put into looking for click lock to drag solutions. You don't need 'em. Just configure the device so you can comfortably hold your primary button while articulating the ball.

9/7/2015
Update. I bought my trackball used. After using it for awhile I noticed that it would sometimes catch inside its cradle causing the cursor to jump. The ball had a small scratch in the plastic. Using a fingernail emery board I smoothed it out then polished with metal polish. Now it's perfect.Great value. Does everything I need it to straight out of the box. product_title: Azio Backlit Mechanical Gaming Keyboard
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:1a0b25f9e643893bcee37005a2b5c923]] The Azio Backlit Mechanical Gaming Keyboard (MGK1-K) is a solid performer. We did receive this keyboard at a reduced cost for out honest opinion/review, we were not compensated to get a positive review the thoughts here are my own. This review is on the MGK1-K. The difference in the MGK1 and the MGK1-K is that the color of the keyboard is now all black (the back is red on the MGK1), The palm rest that is included is now UV coated and they are using Brown switches in the MGK1-K instead of blue switches. If you don't know the difference between blue switches and brown, the brown switches still give that satisfying \\"clack\\" while typing but are not as loud as the blue switches. There is a little difference in \\"Feel\\" but not that much unless your a typing expert and in that case will already know which switches you like better (brown or blue).

Build quality on this keyboard is rock solid, now the keyboard itself is not that heavy weighing in at about 2.3 pounds once the palm rest is attached its is rock solid on your desk (even if you use the tabs in front to elevate the keyboard). Nice brushed aluminum back plate under the keys make it great for the LED lighting to reflect off of. The back lighting is a single color (white) that has 4 levels of brightness, the brightest not being overpowering. Classy look, with out being too underwhelming. You can also active \\"Reactive Mode\\", which is where once you touch a key it will light up and then go out again a second later. The keyboard has a nice 6ft. thick braided USB cable that is also gold plated.

Button layout is spaced nicely with the keys having a nice concave feel to them. There are your tradition \\"media\\" shortcuts in the \\"F\\" keys, you also get a ALT +F9 to lock the windows button on the keyboard so you do not hit it by accident. The number pad is here of course and just above that is a mute button for your system sound. Next to that there is a very cool and practical scroll wheel for your volume control, no more \\"ALT F key a bunch of times to change your volume. Supporting Full USB NKRO on windows (Mac users can still get the 6 KRO).

Overall this keyboard is a very pleasurable experience to type on, not just for gaming but for overall general use as well. This is a great keyboard at a great price. Azio has hit a home run with this keyboard.

product_title: Wacom Intuos Pen and Touch Small Tablet
review_headline: If You Want a Cheap but Good Tablet, This Works
review_body:
I bought this Tablet 2 years ago and seeing as it's finally given up on me I decided to write a review.

It was much cheaper when I bought it ($69) but I still feel as though the newer higher price is still fair. It's a great tablet that's easy to transport and works incredibly well.

However, I encountered a lot of trouble with the USB port in the last couple months of use. First off- the port around the MiniUSB port is very small. I haven't found a good nonWacom Brand cable to replace it. (The Wacom brand cable is $22, a lot more than I'm willing to pay for a USB cable.)
When googling to find an alternative, I learned this tablet is known for having an easily broken USB port. This is apparently easily fixed via soldering but I don't have access to those kinds of materials.

Also, I found the drivers would occasionally switch off while drawing but this is a fairly easy (if not annoying) fix.

product_title: Samsung 128GB Mobile MicroSDXC Card Class 10 High-Speed Micro SDXC upto 48MB / s with Komputerbay SD adaptor and High Speed USB Reader
review_headline: Has only 8GB of memory. Data became corrupted while writing to the card.
review_body: This MicroSDXC card and SD adapter came in what looks like a genuine Samsung package and both the card and reader do at first look like they are genuine Samsung devices. I did not receive a card reader, but I do not need it anyway. I had a lot of trouble inserting the card into the adapter. I attempted to transfer 64GB of files to the card several times and the data kept getting corrupted. The transfer speed to write the files to the card was very slow, and then some of the directories to which I copied the files were empty. Some of the files on the card were okay, and others were corrupted and would not open. I ran a flash card test on the card and it shows that it has only 8GB of memory. I have started the return process. Update: After doing much research, unfortunately I have verified that this is a fake 128GB card that is actually a hacked 8GB card. The controller firmware inside of the card has been modified to show 128GB. The font on the card is not the same font as shown on the Samsung website. (See the attached pictures.) The write speed is about 7MB/s, which is the speed of an SDHC card. The write speed for a typical SDXC card is about 40MB/s. I am using USB 3.0 for data transfer.
